1
00:01:46,325 --> 00:01:48,660
13 meters. You should see it.

2
00:02:02,007 --> 00:02:03,717
Okay, take her up and over the bow rail.

3
00:02:06,178 --> 00:02:09,515
Mir 2, we're going over the bow.
Stay with us.

4
00:02:43,549 --> 00:02:45,717
Okay, quiet. We're rolling.

5
00:02:46,176 --> 00:02:49,513
Seeing her coming out of the
darkness like a ghost ship...

6
00:02:49,763 --> 00:02:51,431
...still gets me every time.

7
00:02:53,183 --> 00:02:57,020
To see the sad ruin of the
great ship sitting here...

8
00:02:57,521 --> 00:02:59,690
...where she landed at
2:30 in the morning

9
00:02:59,898 --> 00:03:01,900
of April 15, 1912...

10
00:03:02,359 --> 00:03:04,528
...after her long fall...

11
00:03:05,320 --> 00:03:07,322
...from the world above.

12
00:03:08,240 --> 00:03:09,408
You are so full of shit, boss.

13
00:03:39,938 --> 00:03:43,609
Dive 6. Here we are again
on the deck of Titanic.

14
00:03:44,067 --> 00:03:47,905
2 1/2 miles down.
3,821 meters.

15
00:03:48,238 --> 00:03:53,243
The pressure outside is 3 1/2 tons per square inch.

16
00:03:54,077 --> 00:03:55,746
These windows are
9 inches thick.

17
00:03:55,996 --> 00:03:59,666
If they go, it's sayonara in two microseconds.

18
00:04:00,209 --> 00:04:02,628
All right, enough of that bullshit.

19
00:04:16,558 --> 00:04:19,978
Just put her down on the roof of
the officers' quarters like yesterday.

20
00:04:21,438 --> 00:04:25,943
Mir 2, we're landing right over the
Grand Staircase. You guys set to launch?

21
00:04:26,276 --> 00:04:29,696
Yeah, Brock. Launching Dunkin now.
Go, Charlie.

22
00:04:37,788 --> 00:04:39,623
- All right, tether out.
- Tether out.

23
00:04:40,499 --> 00:04:43,502
Okay, Brock, we're dropping
down along the hull.

24
00:04:46,129 --> 00:04:50,133
Yeah, roger that. Okay, drop down and go
into the first class gangway door.

25
00:04:50,467 --> 00:04:52,052
I want you guys working the D deck...

26
00:04:52,302 --> 00:04:54,680
...reception area and the dining saloon.

27
00:04:55,472 --> 00:04:56,473
Copy that.

28
00:05:02,688 --> 00:05:05,858
Tether out. Okay, now left. Left, left.
Okay, coming left.

29
00:05:14,867 --> 00:05:18,704
Snoop Dog is on the move.
We're headed down the stairwell.

30
00:05:21,456 --> 00:05:23,292
Okay Lewis, drop down to B deck.

31
00:05:23,792 --> 00:05:26,128
- Okay, A deck.
- Give me some rope, Captain.

32
00:05:26,461 --> 00:05:27,963
B deck. Get in there. Get in there.

33
00:06:06,752 --> 00:06:08,587
Watch the door frame.

34
00:06:08,837 --> 00:06:10,422
- Watch it, watch it.
- I see it. I got it.

35
00:06:16,011 --> 00:06:17,846
- We good? Bring her down.
- We're good. Just chill, boss.

36
00:06:32,277 --> 00:06:34,446
Okay, make your turn.

37
00:06:34,947 --> 00:06:37,199
- Cable out, Captain.
- Make your turn. Watch the wall.

38
00:06:37,491 --> 00:06:39,826
Yeah Brock, we're at the piano.
You copy?

39
00:06:40,452 --> 00:06:41,954
Okay, copy that.

40
00:06:49,336 --> 00:06:51,547
Okay, right there. Right there.

41
00:06:51,839 --> 00:06:53,340
Okay, that's it, that's it.
That's the bedroom door.

42
00:06:53,590 --> 00:06:54,925
I see it. I see it.

43
00:07:04,017 --> 00:07:05,102
We're in!

44
00:07:05,352 --> 00:07:07,521
We're in, baby. We're there.

45
00:07:09,481 --> 00:07:10,566
That's Hockley's bed.

46
00:07:10,691 --> 00:07:12,818
That's where the
son of a bitch slept.

47
00:07:18,907 --> 00:07:21,326
Oops. Somebody left the water running.

48
00:07:21,660 --> 00:07:24,079
Hold it. Hold it just a second.
Go back to the right.

49
00:07:30,711 --> 00:07:33,005
That wardrobe door.
Get closer.

50
00:07:33,422 --> 00:07:34,756
You smelling something, boss?

51
00:07:35,257 --> 00:07:38,177
- I want to see what's under it.
- Give me my hands, man.

52
00:07:44,099 --> 00:07:45,184
All right.

53
00:07:46,852 --> 00:07:48,770
- Take it easy. It might come apart.
- Okay.

54
00:07:50,772 --> 00:07:53,442
Go, go, go. Flip it over.
Flip it over. Go.

55
00:07:54,276 --> 00:07:55,319
Turn her over. Keep going.

56
00:07:55,402 --> 00:07:56,778
Go, go, go.

57
00:07:57,112 --> 00:07:58,197
Okay, drop it.

58
00:08:07,456 --> 00:08:10,542
Oh, baby, baby.
Are you seeing this, boss?

59
00:08:13,462 --> 00:08:15,464
It's payday, boys.

60
00:08:31,271 --> 00:08:32,940
Cha-ching!

61
00:08:33,815 --> 00:08:35,651
- We did it, Bobby.
- We brought it back, Baby.

62
00:08:35,984 --> 00:08:38,987
Oh, yeah! Who's the best?
Who's the best, baby?

63
00:08:39,321 --> 00:08:41,323
Say it. Say it. Say it.

64
00:08:41,657 --> 00:08:43,325
You are, Lewis.

65
00:08:45,911 --> 00:08:46,912
- Bobby, my cigar.
- Right here.

66
00:08:55,838 --> 00:08:56,839
Okay, crack her open.

67
00:09:26,952 --> 00:09:27,953
Shit.

68
00:09:30,205 --> 00:09:31,707
No diamond.

69
00:09:33,750 --> 00:09:37,462
You know boss, this same thing happened
to Geraldo and his career never recovered.

70
00:09:41,550 --> 00:09:42,885
Turn the camera off.

71
00:09:43,218 --> 00:09:45,721
Brock, the partners would like
to know how it's going.

72
00:09:47,222 --> 00:09:51,226
Hey, Dave, Barry, hi. Look, it wasn't
in the safe. But hey, hey...

73
00:09:51,560 --> 00:09:55,063
...Don't worry about it. There's still
plenty of places it could be. Hell, yes.

74
00:09:55,564 --> 00:09:57,691
The floor debris in the suite,
the mother's room...

75
00:09:57,858 --> 00:09:58,942
the purser's safe on C deck.

76
00:09:59,234 --> 00:10:00,319
Jimmy Hoffa's briefcase.

77
00:10:00,569 --> 00:10:05,407
A dozen other places. Guys, look, you're just
going to have to trust my instincts. I know we're close.

78
00:10:05,657 --> 00:10:07,993
We've just got to go through a little
process of elimination.

79
00:10:09,411 --> 00:10:11,079
Hang on a second.

80
00:10:14,249 --> 00:10:16,001
- Let me see that.
- Ah, we may have something here, guys.

81
00:10:19,755 --> 00:10:21,507
Where's the photograph
of the necklace?

82
00:10:21,590 --> 00:10:22,591
We'll call you right back.

83
00:10:34,603 --> 00:10:36,438
I'll be goddamned.

84
00:10:39,358 --> 00:10:42,861
Treasure hunter Brock Lovett
is best known for finding Spanish gold...

85
00:10:43,111 --> 00:10:44,780
It's okay. I'll feed you in a minute.

86
00:10:45,113 --> 00:10:50,118
Now he has chartered Russian subs to reach
the most famous shipwreck of all, the Titanic.

87
00:10:50,452 --> 00:10:54,289
He is with us live via satellite
from the research ship Keldysh...

88
00:10:54,540 --> 00:10:56,708
...in the North Atlantic. Hello, Brock.

89
00:10:56,959 --> 00:11:00,963
Hello, Tracy. Of course, everyone knows
the familiar stories of Titanic.

90
00:11:01,213 --> 00:11:04,216
You know, the nobility of the
band playing to the very end and all that.

91
00:11:04,466 --> 00:11:08,971
But what I'm interested in are the untold stories.
The secrets locked deep inside the hull of Titanic.

92
00:11:09,221 --> 00:11:13,225
And we're out here using robot
technology to go further into the wreck...

93
00:11:13,475 --> 00:11:15,143
...than anybody has ever done before.

94
00:11:15,477 --> 00:11:18,647
Your expedition is at the center
of a storm of controversy...

95
00:11:18,897 --> 00:11:22,901
...over salvage rights and even ethics.
Many are calling you a graverobber.

96
00:11:23,151 --> 00:11:24,987
Well, nobody ever called the
recovery of the artifacts...

97
00:11:25,237 --> 00:11:26,238
What is it?

98
00:11:26,488 --> 00:11:28,156
Turn that up, dear.

99
00:11:28,490 --> 00:11:31,159
I have museum-trained experts
sent out here making sure...

100
00:11:31,410 --> 00:11:34,079
...that these relics are preserved
and catalogued properly.

101
00:11:34,246 --> 00:11:37,082
Take a look at this drawing
that we found just today.

102
00:11:37,332 --> 00:11:40,836
A piece of paper that's been underwater
for 84 years.

103
00:11:41,170 --> 00:11:43,672
And my team are able to
preserve it intact.

104
00:11:44,173 --> 00:11:47,342
Should this have remained unseen
at the bottom of the ocean for eternity...

105
00:11:47,593 --> 00:11:49,595
...when we can see and enjoy it now?

106
00:11:49,845 --> 00:11:51,680
I'll be goddamned.

107
00:11:55,100 --> 00:11:56,101
Brock!

108
00:11:56,685 --> 00:11:58,353
There's a satellite call for you.

109
00:11:58,604 --> 00:12:01,940
Bobby, we're launching. You see
these submersibles going in the water?

110
00:12:02,191 --> 00:12:04,610
Trust me, buddy.
You want to take this call.

111
00:12:05,944 --> 00:12:07,779
This better be good.

112
00:12:08,113 --> 00:12:10,782
Now, you gotta speak up.
She's kind of old.

113
00:12:11,033 --> 00:12:12,201
Great.

114
00:12:13,702 --> 00:12:16,455
This is Brock Lovett.
How can I help you, Mrs...?

115
00:12:16,705 --> 00:12:18,707
Calvert. Rose Calvert.

116
00:12:18,832 --> 00:12:19,833
Mrs. Calvert.

117
00:12:20,876 --> 00:12:23,795
I was just wondering if you had found...

118
00:12:24,046 --> 00:12:26,048
...the "Heart of the Ocean" yet, Mr. Lovett.

119
00:12:28,383 --> 00:12:30,135
Told you you wanted to take the call.

120
00:12:32,387 --> 00:12:35,390
All right, you have my
attention, Rose.

121
00:12:35,724 --> 00:12:37,976
Can you tell us who the woman
in the picture is?

122
00:12:38,393 --> 00:12:41,730
Oh, yes. The woman in the picture is me.

123
00:12:58,163 --> 00:13:02,334
She's a goddamn liar!
Some nutcase seeking money or publicity.

124
00:13:02,751 --> 00:13:06,421
God only knows why.
Like that Russian babe, Anesthesia.

125
00:13:06,755 --> 00:13:08,590
They're inbound!

126
00:13:13,595 --> 00:13:17,516
Rose DeWitt Bukater died on the
Titanic when she was 17, right?

127
00:13:18,433 --> 00:13:21,270
- That's right.
- If she had lived, she'd be over 100 by now.

128
00:13:21,603 --> 00:13:23,772
101 next month.

129
00:13:24,106 --> 00:13:26,942
Okay, so she's a very old goddamn liar.

130
00:13:27,192 --> 00:13:29,361
Look, I've already done the
background on this woman...

131
00:13:29,611 --> 00:13:33,448
...all the way back to the 20s,
when she was working as an actress.

132
00:13:33,782 --> 00:13:36,618
An actress.
There's your first clue, Sherlock.

133
00:13:36,952 --> 00:13:41,248
Her name was Rose Dawson back then.
Then she marries this guy named Calvert.

134
00:13:41,456 --> 00:13:44,793
They move to Cedar Rapids
and she punches out a couple of kids.

135
00:13:45,127 --> 00:13:48,297
Now Calvert's dead
and, from what I hear, Cedar Rapids is dead.

136
00:13:48,547 --> 00:13:50,883
And everybody who knows about the
diamond is supposed to be dead...

137
00:13:51,091 --> 00:13:53,093
...or on this boat,
but she knows.

138
00:14:06,481 --> 00:14:09,067
Doesn't exactly travel light, does she?

139
00:14:09,443 --> 00:14:10,485
Hurry up, give him a hand.

140
00:14:11,236 --> 00:14:14,907
Mrs. Calvert, I'm Brock Lovett.
Welcome to the Keldysh.

141
00:14:17,159 --> 00:14:18,994
Okay, let's get her inside there.

142
00:14:19,495 --> 00:14:20,496
Hi, Miss Calvert.

143
00:14:21,163 --> 00:14:22,748
- Hi.
- Welcome to the Keldysh.

144
00:14:23,499 --> 00:14:24,833
Thanks.

145
00:14:26,502 --> 00:14:27,503
Hey!

146
00:14:35,677 --> 00:14:37,095
Are your staterooms
all right?

147
00:14:37,179 --> 00:14:38,180
Oh, yes.

148
00:14:38,305 --> 00:14:39,348
Very nice.

149
00:14:39,598 --> 00:14:41,600
Have you met my
granddaughter, Lizzy?

150
00:14:41,725 --> 00:14:43,310
She takes care of me.

151
00:14:44,269 --> 00:14:46,313
We met just a few
minutes ago.

152
00:14:46,438 --> 00:14:47,648
Remember, Nana?
Up on deck?

153
00:14:47,940 --> 00:14:49,024
Oh, yes.

154
00:14:50,067 --> 00:14:51,610
There. That's nice.

155
00:14:52,277 --> 00:14:54,530
Have to have my
pictures when I travel.

156
00:14:54,696 --> 00:14:55,697
Can I get you anything?

157
00:14:55,781 --> 00:14:57,032
Is there anything you'd like?

158
00:14:58,617 --> 00:14:59,785
Yes.

159
00:15:00,285 --> 00:15:02,621
I would like to
see my drawing.

160
00:15:16,468 --> 00:15:19,388
Louis XVI wore a fabulous
stone that was...

161
00:15:19,596 --> 00:15:21,181
...called the Blue Diamond
of the Crown...

162
00:15:21,473 --> 00:15:24,142
...which disappeared
in 1792...

163
00:15:24,393 --> 00:15:28,063
...about the same time old Louis lost
everything from the neck up.

164
00:15:28,647 --> 00:15:32,150
The theory goes that the
crown diamond was chopped, too.

165
00:15:32,985 --> 00:15:34,653
Recut into a heart-like shape that
became known as...

166
00:15:35,362 --> 00:15:36,864
...the Heart of the Ocean.

167
00:15:37,072 --> 00:15:39,741
Today it would be worth
more than the Hope diamond.

168
00:15:39,992 --> 00:15:42,161
It was a dreadful,
heavy thing.

169
00:15:42,494 --> 00:15:44,496
I only wore it this once.

170
00:15:45,247 --> 00:15:47,082
You actually think
this is you, Nana?

171
00:15:47,332 --> 00:15:49,209
It is me, dear.

172
00:15:49,459 --> 00:15:51,211
Wasn't I a dish?

173
00:15:53,255 --> 00:15:55,924
I tracked it down
through insurance records.

174
00:15:56,175 --> 00:15:59,928
An old claim that was settled
under terms of absolute secrecy.

175
00:16:01,013 --> 00:16:03,682
Can you tell me who the
claimant was, Rose?

176
00:16:04,016 --> 00:16:06,602
I should imagine someone
named Hockley.

177
00:16:07,019 --> 00:16:08,645
Nathan Hockley,
that's right.

178
00:16:09,271 --> 00:16:11,106
Pittsburgh steel tycoon.

179
00:16:11,356 --> 00:16:13,734
The claim was for a
diamond necklace his son...

180
00:16:13,817 --> 00:16:15,277
...Caledon, bought his fiancée.

181
00:16:15,694 --> 00:16:16,695
You.

182
00:16:17,112 --> 00:16:19,364
A week before he
sailed on Titanic.

183
00:16:20,365 --> 00:16:22,701
And it was filed right
after the sinking.

184
00:16:23,535 --> 00:16:26,622
So the diamond had to have
gone down with the ship.

185
00:16:28,040 --> 00:16:29,208
You see the date?

186
00:16:30,709 --> 00:16:32,711
April 14, 1912.

187
00:16:33,045 --> 00:16:35,881
Which means if your grandmother
is who she says she is...

188
00:16:36,131 --> 00:16:38,800
...she was wearing the diamond
the day the Titanic sank.

189
00:16:39,051 --> 00:16:42,179
And that makes you
my new best friend.

190
00:16:43,055 --> 00:16:45,182
These are some of the things
we recovered from your stateroom.

191
00:16:48,727 --> 00:16:50,562
This was mine.

192
00:16:51,730 --> 00:16:53,899
How extraordinary.

193
00:16:54,566 --> 00:16:57,986
And it looks the same as it
did the last time I saw it.

194
00:17:03,742 --> 00:17:06,245
The reflection has
changed a bit.

195
00:17:22,761 --> 00:17:25,430
Are you ready to go
back to Titanic?

196
00:17:28,976 --> 00:17:30,185
Okay, here we go.

197
00:17:30,394 --> 00:17:33,480
She hits the berg on
the starboard side, right?

198
00:17:33,564 --> 00:17:34,565
She kind of bumps along...

199
00:17:34,648 --> 00:17:35,899
...punching holes like
morse code...

200
00:17:36,149 --> 00:17:37,442
dit-dit-dit... along the side...

201
00:17:37,526 --> 00:17:38,527
...below the water line.

202
00:17:38,610 --> 00:17:42,281
Then the forward compartments
start to flood.

203
00:17:42,531 --> 00:17:43,657
Now, as the water
level rises...

204
00:17:43,782 --> 00:17:45,659
...it spills over the
watertight bulkheads...

205
00:17:45,868 --> 00:17:48,537
...which, unfortunately, don't go
any higher than E deck.

206
00:17:48,704 --> 00:17:50,372
So now as the
bow goes down...

207
00:17:50,622 --> 00:17:53,125
...the stern rises up,
slow at first...

208
00:17:53,208 --> 00:17:54,793
...then faster and faster...

209
00:17:55,127 --> 00:17:57,296
...until finally, she's got her whole
ass sticking up in the air.

210
00:17:58,297 --> 00:17:59,339
And that's a big ass.

211
00:18:00,174 --> 00:18:02,301
We're talking
20, 30,000 tons. Okay?

212
00:18:02,551 --> 00:18:04,636
And the hull's not designed
to deal with that pressure.

213
00:18:04,720 --> 00:18:06,430
So, what happens?

214
00:18:06,889 --> 00:18:08,599
She splits, right
down to the keel.

215
00:18:08,682 --> 00:18:09,683
And the stern...

216
00:18:10,142 --> 00:18:11,143
...falls back level.

217
00:18:11,226 --> 00:18:12,227
Then...

218
00:18:12,311 --> 00:18:13,312
...as the bow sinks...

219
00:18:13,395 --> 00:18:15,314
...it pulls the stern vertical...

220
00:18:15,397 --> 00:18:17,566
...and then finally detaches.

221
00:18:17,816 --> 00:18:21,653
Now the stern section just kind of bobs
there like a cork for a couple of minutes...

222
00:18:21,904 --> 00:18:25,073
...floods, and finally goes
under about 2:20 AM...

223
00:18:25,324 --> 00:18:27,493
...2 hours and 40 minutes
after the collision.

224
00:18:28,994 --> 00:18:30,329
The bow section
planes away...

225
00:18:30,621 --> 00:18:33,290
...landing about a
half a mile away...

226
00:18:33,624 --> 00:18:35,375
...going 20, 30 knots when
it hits the ocean floor.

227
00:18:39,671 --> 00:18:41,256
Pretty cool, huh?

228
00:18:41,507 --> 00:18:45,844
Thank you for that fine
forensic analysis, Mr. Bodine.

229
00:18:46,678 --> 00:18:50,015
Of course, the
experience of it was...

230
00:18:50,849 --> 00:18:52,518
...somewhat different.

231
00:18:53,018 --> 00:18:55,020
Will you share it with us?

232
00:19:49,950 --> 00:19:50,993
I'm taking her to rest.

233
00:19:51,076 --> 00:19:52,077
No.

234
00:19:52,161 --> 00:19:53,412
Come on, Nana.

235
00:19:53,495 --> 00:19:54,830
No!

236
00:19:58,917 --> 00:20:00,586
Give me the
tape recorder.

237
00:20:03,589 --> 00:20:04,756
Tell us, Rose.

238
00:20:06,758 --> 00:20:08,927
It's been 84 years...

239
00:20:09,761 --> 00:20:11,054
It's okay. Just try
to remember anything...

240
00:20:11,221 --> 00:20:12,639
...anything at all.

241
00:20:13,765 --> 00:20:16,602
Do you want to hear this
or not, Mr. Lovett?

242
00:20:20,606 --> 00:20:23,609
It's been 84 years...

243
00:20:25,444 --> 00:20:28,447
...and I can still smell
the fresh paint.

244
00:20:30,240 --> 00:20:33,076
The china had
never been used.

245
00:20:33,785 --> 00:20:36,455
The sheets had
never been slept in.

246
00:20:38,123 --> 00:20:42,044
Titanic was called
the ship of dreams.

247
00:20:43,545 --> 00:20:44,713
And it was.

248
00:20:45,964 --> 00:20:47,674
It really was.

249
00:21:18,038 --> 00:21:19,414
All third-class
passengers...

250
00:21:20,207 --> 00:21:21,625
...with a forward berth...

251
00:21:21,750 --> 00:21:24,044
...this way please!
This queue!

252
00:21:24,586 --> 00:21:26,088
It's a big boat, huh?

253
00:21:26,338 --> 00:21:28,298
Daddy, it's a ship.

254
00:21:28,423 --> 00:21:29,424
You're right.

255
00:21:59,454 --> 00:22:01,415
I don't see what all
the fuss is about.

256
00:22:02,040 --> 00:22:04,042
It doesn't look any bigger
than the Mauretania.

257
00:22:04,293 --> 00:22:05,961
You can be blasé
about some things, Rose...

258
00:22:06,128 --> 00:22:07,880
...but not about Titanic.

259
00:22:08,130 --> 00:22:09,840
It's over 100 feet longer
than Mauretania...

260
00:22:09,923 --> 00:22:11,466
...and far more luxurious.

261
00:22:12,301 --> 00:22:14,761
Your daughter is far too
difficult to impress, Ruth.

262
00:22:15,721 --> 00:22:18,015
So this is the ship they
say is unsinkable.

263
00:22:18,098 --> 00:22:19,141
It is unsinkable.

264
00:22:19,224 --> 00:22:20,642
God Himself
could not sink this ship...

265
00:22:20,726 --> 00:22:21,768
What?!

266
00:22:21,852 --> 00:22:23,353
You have to check your baggage
through the main terminal.

267
00:22:23,437 --> 00:22:24,646
It's round that
way, sir.

268
00:22:25,063 --> 00:22:26,481
I put my faith in
you good sir.

269
00:22:26,565 --> 00:22:27,691
Now kindly
see my man.

270
00:22:27,900 --> 00:22:29,026
Yes sir. It's my
pleasure, sir.

271
00:22:29,109 --> 00:22:30,152
If I can do
anything at all...

272
00:22:30,235 --> 00:22:31,570
Yes, right.

273
00:22:31,904 --> 00:22:33,822
All the trunks from
that car there.

274
00:22:33,906 --> 00:22:35,949
12 from here.

275
00:22:36,241 --> 00:22:39,077
And the safe,
to the parlor suite...

276
00:22:39,161 --> 00:22:40,913
...rooms B-52, 54, 56.

277
00:22:43,248 --> 00:22:44,249
Ladies...

278
00:22:44,458 --> 00:22:46,084
...we better hurry.

279
00:22:46,376 --> 00:22:47,377
Come along.

280
00:22:51,882 --> 00:22:53,133
- My coat?
- I have it, miss.

281
00:22:56,386 --> 00:23:00,557
All third-class passengers
queue here for health inspection.

282
00:23:06,730 --> 00:23:09,233
- Welcome aboard, ma'am.
- Welcome to Titanic.

283
00:23:10,692 --> 00:23:12,528
It was the ship of dreams...

284
00:23:12,611 --> 00:23:13,987
...to everyone else.

285
00:23:14,780 --> 00:23:17,282
To me, it was a
slave ship...

286
00:23:17,616 --> 00:23:20,786
...taking me back to
America in chains.

287
00:23:21,787 --> 00:23:25,791
Outwardly, I was everything
a well brought up girl should be.

288
00:23:26,124 --> 00:23:28,627
Inside, I was screaming.

289
00:23:45,143 --> 00:23:46,395
Jack, you are pazzo.

290
00:23:46,478 --> 00:23:48,313
You bet everything
we have.

291
00:23:49,398 --> 00:23:51,650
When you got nothing,
you got nothing to lose.

292
00:23:59,074 --> 00:24:00,117
Sven?

293
00:24:21,847 --> 00:24:24,183
All right,
moment of truth.

294
00:24:24,516 --> 00:24:26,685
Someone's life is
about to change.

295
00:24:26,894 --> 00:24:28,061
Fabrizio?

296
00:24:30,397 --> 00:24:31,398
Niente.

297
00:24:31,481 --> 00:24:32,524
Niente.

298
00:24:33,692 --> 00:24:34,693
Olaf?

299
00:24:35,694 --> 00:24:36,862
Nothing.

300
00:24:37,196 --> 00:24:38,363
Sven?

301
00:24:41,200 --> 00:24:43,869
Uh-oh.
2 pair.

302
00:24:44,703 --> 00:24:46,121
I'm sorry,
Fabrizio.

303
00:24:48,290 --> 00:24:49,333
I'm sorry...

304
00:24:49,500 --> 00:24:50,667
...you're not gonna see
your mom again for a...

305
00:24:51,126 --> 00:24:52,711
...long time...

306
00:24:52,794 --> 00:24:54,463
...'cause we're
going to America.

307
00:24:54,755 --> 00:24:55,839
Full house, boys!

308
00:25:10,062 --> 00:25:11,230
Come on.

309
00:25:12,147 --> 00:25:13,732
I'm going home!

310
00:25:16,527 --> 00:25:18,153
I'm going home.

311
00:25:18,278 --> 00:25:19,613
I go to America!

312
00:25:19,905 --> 00:25:21,240
No, mate.

313
00:25:21,573 --> 00:25:23,492
Titanic go to America,

314
00:25:23,575 --> 00:25:25,077
in 5 minutes.

315
00:25:25,577 --> 00:25:26,620
Shit. Fabri.
Come on.

316
00:25:26,703 --> 00:25:27,746
Come on,
here. Here.

317
00:25:30,165 --> 00:25:31,959
We're riding in
high style now!

318
00:25:32,751 --> 00:25:34,503
We're a couple of
regular swells.

319
00:25:34,670 --> 00:25:36,296
We're practically
goddamn royalty...

320
00:25:36,380 --> 00:25:37,381
...ragazzo mio.

321
00:25:37,589 --> 00:25:39,591
You see?
Is my destino.

322
00:25:40,050 --> 00:25:41,134
Like I told you...

323
00:25:41,218 --> 00:25:42,970
I go to America to
be millionaire.

324
00:25:46,265 --> 00:25:47,349
You are pazzo.

325
00:25:47,516 --> 00:25:49,184
Maybe, but I've
got the tickets.

326
00:25:51,019 --> 00:25:52,521
Come on, I thought
you were fast.

327
00:25:52,604 --> 00:25:53,605
Aspetta!

328
00:25:54,189 --> 00:25:55,607
Whoa. Wait! Wait!

329
00:25:55,691 --> 00:25:56,692
Hey, wait!

330
00:25:57,234 --> 00:25:58,235
We're passengers!

331
00:26:01,113 --> 00:26:02,406
Have you been through
the inspection queue?

332
00:26:02,489 --> 00:26:03,490
Of course.

333
00:26:03,574 --> 00:26:05,033
Anyway, we
don't have any lice.

334
00:26:05,159 --> 00:26:07,035
We're Americans.
Both of us.

335
00:26:07,119 --> 00:26:08,120
Right.

336
00:26:08,203 --> 00:26:09,204
Come aboard.

337
00:26:13,458 --> 00:26:15,127
We're the luckiest sons
of bitches in the world.

338
00:26:15,169 --> 00:26:16,170
You know that?

339
00:26:25,304 --> 00:26:26,388
Good-bye!

340
00:26:30,434 --> 00:26:31,476
You know somebody?

341
00:26:31,560 --> 00:26:33,061
Of course not.
That's not the point.

342
00:26:33,312 --> 00:26:34,646
Good-bye!
I'll miss you!

343
00:26:34,980 --> 00:26:36,106
Good-bye!

344
00:26:36,565 --> 00:26:38,275
I will never forget you!

345
00:27:26,532 --> 00:27:28,492
Come with me,
darling. Let's go.

346
00:27:31,036 --> 00:27:32,371
G-60.

347
00:27:33,372 --> 00:27:35,040
G-60. G-60.

348
00:27:35,374 --> 00:27:36,458
Excuse me,
ma'am.

349
00:27:37,376 --> 00:27:38,710
G-60.

350
00:27:40,045 --> 00:27:41,713
Oh, right here.

351
00:27:42,214 --> 00:27:43,298
Hey, how you doing?

352
00:27:43,507 --> 00:27:45,425
Jack. Nice
to meet you.

353
00:27:45,717 --> 00:27:47,219
Jack Dawson.
Nice to meet you.

354
00:27:47,678 --> 00:27:48,679
How you doing?

355
00:27:49,388 --> 00:27:51,723
Who says you get
top bunk, huh?

356
00:27:57,354 --> 00:27:59,481
This is your private
promenade deck, sir.

357
00:27:59,606 --> 00:28:01,859
Will you be requiring
anything?

358
00:28:02,067 --> 00:28:03,402
Excuse me.

359
00:28:03,819 --> 00:28:05,487
- This one?
- No.

360
00:28:05,737 --> 00:28:07,990
It had a lot of faces on it.

361
00:28:08,407 --> 00:28:09,908
This is the one.

362
00:28:11,577 --> 00:28:13,412
Would you like all of
them out, miss?

363
00:28:13,745 --> 00:28:16,915
Yes. We need a little
color in this room.

364
00:28:20,544 --> 00:28:21,962
Put in there.
In the wardrobe.

365
00:28:22,921 --> 00:28:25,174
God, not those finger
paintings again.

366
00:28:25,424 --> 00:28:26,842
They certainly were a
waste of money.

367
00:28:27,092 --> 00:28:28,927
The difference between
Cal's taste in art...

368
00:28:29,011 --> 00:28:30,596
...and mine is that I have some.

369
00:28:30,679 --> 00:28:31,680
They're fascinating.

370
00:28:32,764 --> 00:28:35,184
Like being inside a dream
or something.

371
00:28:35,434 --> 00:28:36,768
There's truth but no logic.

372
00:28:37,019 --> 00:28:39,855
- What's the artist's name?
- Something Picasso.

373
00:28:40,105 --> 00:28:41,315
Something Picasso.

374
00:28:41,398 --> 00:28:43,150
He won't amount
to a thing.

375
00:28:43,233 --> 00:28:44,484
He won't, trust me.

376
00:28:44,776 --> 00:28:47,029
- Let's put the Degas in the bedroom.
- At least they were cheap.

377
00:28:47,779 --> 00:28:49,615
Put it in the wardrobe.

378
00:28:55,120 --> 00:28:59,458
At Cherbourg, a woman came aboard
named Margaret Brown.

379
00:28:59,791 --> 00:29:01,460
We all called her Molly.

380
00:29:01,793 --> 00:29:04,963
History would call her
the Unsinkable Molly Brown.

381
00:29:05,297 --> 00:29:07,424
Well, I wasn't about to
wait all day for you, sonny.

382
00:29:07,549 --> 00:29:09,676
Here, if you think
you can manage.

383
00:29:10,302 --> 00:29:13,305
Her husband had struck gold
someplace out west.

384
00:29:13,639 --> 00:29:16,433
And she was what Mother
called "new money".

385
00:29:17,643 --> 00:29:18,936
By the next afternoon...

386
00:29:19,019 --> 00:29:21,730
...we were steaming west
from the coast of Ireland...

387
00:29:22,606 --> 00:29:26,109
...with nothing out ahead
of us but ocean.

388
00:29:32,324 --> 00:29:34,493
Take her to sea,
Mr. Murdoch.

389
00:29:35,410 --> 00:29:36,620
Let's stretch her legs.

390
00:29:37,079 --> 00:29:38,080
Yes sir.

391
00:29:40,332 --> 00:29:41,375
All ahead full, Mr. Moody.

392
00:29:42,125 --> 00:29:43,168
Very good, sir.

393
00:29:48,632 --> 00:29:49,758
All ahead full.

394
00:29:50,467 --> 00:29:51,885
All ahead full!

395
00:29:52,719 --> 00:29:53,929
Come on lads,
step lively!

396
00:30:12,447 --> 00:30:14,575
All right! Let's stoke
her right up!

397
00:30:14,783 --> 00:30:15,993
We go full ahead!

398
00:30:16,326 --> 00:30:18,328
Come on, put your
backs into it!

399
00:31:13,091 --> 00:31:14,927
21 knots, sir.

400
00:31:23,852 --> 00:31:24,853
Hey, look,
look, look!

401
00:31:28,106 --> 00:31:29,441
See it?

402
00:31:32,778 --> 00:31:34,780
There's another
one! See him?

403
00:31:45,165 --> 00:31:46,959
Look at that one!
Look at him jump!

404
00:32:13,569 --> 00:32:15,821
I can see the Statue
of Liberty already.

405
00:32:16,155 --> 00:32:17,573
Very small,
of course.

406
00:32:21,160 --> 00:32:23,996
I'm the king
of the world!

407
00:33:10,042 --> 00:33:13,045
She is the largest moving object
ever made by the hand of man...

408
00:33:13,295 --> 00:33:15,297
...in all history.

409
00:33:15,631 --> 00:33:17,758
And our master shipbuilder,
Mr. Andrews here...

410
00:33:17,841 --> 00:33:19,718
...designed her from the
keel plates up.

411
00:33:19,968 --> 00:33:21,929
I may have knocked
her together, but...

412
00:33:22,095 --> 00:33:24,181
...the idea was
Mr. Ismay's.

413
00:33:24,640 --> 00:33:27,017
He envisioned a steamer
so grand in scale...

414
00:33:27,100 --> 00:33:28,143
...and so luxurious in...

415
00:33:28,227 --> 00:33:29,269
...its appointments...

416
00:33:29,353 --> 00:33:31,480
...that its supremacy
would never be challenged.

417
00:33:31,647 --> 00:33:33,148
And here she is.

418
00:33:33,398 --> 00:33:36,693
- Willed into solid reality.
- Hear, hear.

419
00:33:37,861 --> 00:33:39,404
I'll have the salmon.

420
00:33:42,407 --> 00:33:44,910
You know I don't
like that, Rose.

421
00:33:48,413 --> 00:33:49,748
She knows.

422
00:33:52,584 --> 00:33:54,086
We'll both have
the lamb.

423
00:33:54,169 --> 00:33:56,338
Rare, with very
little mint sauce.

424
00:33:57,422 --> 00:33:59,007
You like lamb,
right sweet pea?

425
00:34:01,677 --> 00:34:03,846
You gonna cut her meat
for her too there, Cal?

426
00:34:06,431 --> 00:34:09,268
Hey, who thought of
the name Titanic?

427
00:34:10,102 --> 00:34:11,103
Was it you,
Bruce?

428
00:34:11,270 --> 00:34:12,604
Yes, actually.

429
00:34:13,438 --> 00:34:17,609
I wanted to convey sheer size.
And size means stability...

430
00:34:18,110 --> 00:34:21,113
...luxury, and above
all, strength.

431
00:34:21,947 --> 00:34:24,449
Do you know of
Dr. Freud, Mr. Ismay?

432
00:34:24,700 --> 00:34:29,037
His ideas about the male preoccupation
with size might be of particular interest to you.

433
00:34:30,455 --> 00:34:31,790
What's gotten into you?

434
00:34:32,040 --> 00:34:33,375
Excuse me.

435
00:34:37,963 --> 00:34:39,298
I do apologize.

436
00:34:39,548 --> 00:34:41,592
She's a pistol, Cal.
Hope you can handle her.

437
00:34:42,467 --> 00:34:46,221
Well, I may have to start minding what she
reads from now on, won't I, Mrs. Brown?

438
00:34:46,638 --> 00:34:49,391
Freud? Who is he?
Is he a passenger?

439
00:35:01,695 --> 00:35:03,530
The ship is nice, huh?

440
00:35:04,531 --> 00:35:05,532
Yeah. It's an Irish ship.

441
00:35:05,657 --> 00:35:06,658
Is English, no?

442
00:35:06,783 --> 00:35:07,784
No, it was built
in Ireland.

443
00:35:07,868 --> 00:35:09,703
15,000 Irishmen
built this ship.

444
00:35:09,870 --> 00:35:12,539
Solid as a rock.
Big Irish hands.

445
00:35:13,207 --> 00:35:14,208
That's typical.

446
00:35:14,333 --> 00:35:17,377
First-class dogs
come down here to take a shite.

447
00:35:18,128 --> 00:35:20,172
Lets us know where we rank
in the scheme of things.

448
00:35:20,380 --> 00:35:22,049
Like we could forget?

449
00:35:23,717 --> 00:35:24,885
I'm Tommy Ryan.

450
00:35:25,177 --> 00:35:27,221
- Jack Dawson.
- Fabrizio.

451
00:35:29,306 --> 00:35:30,849
Do you make any money
with your drawings?

452
00:35:41,902 --> 00:35:43,570
Ah, forget it, boyo.

453
00:35:43,654 --> 00:35:45,906
You'd as like have angels fly out of
your arse as get next to...

454
00:35:46,073 --> 00:35:47,574
...the likes of her.

455
00:36:10,931 --> 00:36:14,935
I saw my whole life
as if I'd already lived it.

456
00:36:15,269 --> 00:36:18,772
An endless parade
of parties and cotillions...

457
00:36:19,106 --> 00:36:21,108
...yachts and polo matches.

458
00:36:21,775 --> 00:36:26,446
Always the same narrow people,
the same mindless chatter.

459
00:36:26,947 --> 00:36:30,784
I felt like I was standing
at a great precipice...

460
00:36:31,451 --> 00:36:35,622
...with no one to pull me back.
No one who cared...

461
00:36:35,956 --> 00:36:38,125
...or even noticed.

462
00:38:28,694 --> 00:38:29,695
Don't do it.

463
00:38:30,737 --> 00:38:32,072
Stay back.

464
00:38:33,073 --> 00:38:34,074
Don't come any closer.

465
00:38:35,826 --> 00:38:36,869
Come on.

466
00:38:36,910 --> 00:38:38,328
Just give me your hand.
I'll pull you back over.

467
00:38:38,537 --> 00:38:39,746
No!
Stay where you are.

468
00:38:41,081 --> 00:38:42,082
I mean it.

469
00:38:42,749 --> 00:38:44,418
I'll let go.

470
00:38:55,429 --> 00:38:56,930
No, you won't.

471
00:38:58,432 --> 00:39:00,267
What do you mean,
no I won't?

472
00:39:00,559 --> 00:39:03,228
Don't presume to tell me
what I will and will not do.

473
00:39:03,353 --> 00:39:04,438
You don't know me.

474
00:39:04,605 --> 00:39:06,773
Well, you would have done it already.

475
00:39:07,441 --> 00:39:09,610
You're distracting me.
Go away.

476
00:39:09,943 --> 00:39:11,111
I can't.

477
00:39:11,278 --> 00:39:12,529
I'm involved now.

478
00:39:13,447 --> 00:39:16,783
You let go, and I'm going to have
to jump in there after you.

479
00:39:18,619 --> 00:39:20,120
Don't be absurd.

480
00:39:20,454 --> 00:39:22,623
- You'll be killed.
- I'm a good swimmer.

481
00:39:22,956 --> 00:39:24,791
The fall alone will kill you.

482
00:39:25,125 --> 00:39:28,295
It would hurt. I'm not
saying it wouldn't.

483
00:39:28,962 --> 00:39:30,088
Tell you the truth...

484
00:39:30,589 --> 00:39:33,217
...I'm a lot more concerned
about that water being so cold.

485
00:39:40,307 --> 00:39:41,600
How cold?

486
00:39:41,975 --> 00:39:45,145
Freezing.
Maybe a couple degrees over.

487
00:39:49,650 --> 00:39:50,651
You ever, uh...

488
00:39:50,984 --> 00:39:52,736
...ever been
to Wisconsin?

489
00:39:55,989 --> 00:39:57,157
What?

490
00:39:57,449 --> 00:39:59,660
Well, they have some of
the coldest winters around.

491
00:40:00,160 --> 00:40:02,830
I grew up there,
near Chippewa Falls.

492
00:40:03,163 --> 00:40:06,834
I remember when I was a kid,
me and my father, we went ice fishing...

493
00:40:07,167 --> 00:40:09,002
...out on Lake Wissota.

494
00:40:09,586 --> 00:40:10,838
Ice fishing is, you know, where you...

495
00:40:11,171 --> 00:40:12,756
I know what ice fishing is!

496
00:40:14,007 --> 00:40:15,175
Sorry.

497
00:40:16,343 --> 00:40:20,013
You just seem like, you know,
kind of an indoor girl.

498
00:40:22,015 --> 00:40:23,350
Anyway, I...

499
00:40:24,685 --> 00:40:26,353
...fell through some thin ice.

500
00:40:26,854 --> 00:40:28,188
And I'm telling you...

501
00:40:29,857 --> 00:40:31,191
...water that cold,

502
00:40:31,316 --> 00:40:33,193
like right down there...

503
00:40:33,986 --> 00:40:37,322
...it hits you like 1000 knives
stabbing you all over your body.

504
00:40:38,824 --> 00:40:40,159
You can't breathe.

505
00:40:41,201 --> 00:40:45,664
You can't think. Least not about
anything but the pain.

506
00:40:48,709 --> 00:40:51,962
Which is why I'm not looking
forward to jumping in there after you.

507
00:40:53,046 --> 00:40:54,047
Like I said...

508
00:40:55,883 --> 00:40:57,551
...I don't have a choice.

509
00:41:01,722 --> 00:41:04,558
I guess I'm kind of hoping you'll
come back over the rail and...

510
00:41:04,641 --> 00:41:06,059
...and get me off
the hook here.

511
00:41:06,894 --> 00:41:08,228
You're crazy.

512
00:41:09,563 --> 00:41:11,732
That's what everybody says but...

513
00:41:13,233 --> 00:41:14,902
...with all due respect, miss...

514
00:41:14,985 --> 00:41:17,738
...I'm not the one hanging off
the back of a ship here.

515
00:41:18,572 --> 00:41:19,907
Come on.

516
00:41:20,574 --> 00:41:22,242
Come on, give me your hand.

517
00:41:23,160 --> 00:41:24,411
You don't want to do this.

518
00:41:40,427 --> 00:41:41,929
I'm Jack Dawson.

519
00:41:43,430 --> 00:41:45,098
Rose DeWitt Bukater.

520
00:41:45,390 --> 00:41:47,100
I'll have to get you to
write that one down.

521
00:41:49,603 --> 00:41:50,771
Come on.

522
00:41:56,068 --> 00:41:57,069
I got you.

523
00:41:57,569 --> 00:41:58,570
Come on.

524
00:41:58,946 --> 00:42:00,280
Come on.

525
00:42:04,743 --> 00:42:06,078
Help, please!

526
00:42:06,370 --> 00:42:07,955
Help!

527
00:42:09,414 --> 00:42:10,457
- Please, help me!
- Listen. Listen to me.

528
00:42:10,582 --> 00:42:12,125
Listen. Listen to me.

529
00:42:12,292 --> 00:42:13,961
I've got you.
I won't let go.

530
00:42:14,253 --> 00:42:16,255
Now pull yourself up.
Come on!

531
00:42:19,299 --> 00:42:20,300
Come on.

532
00:42:20,551 --> 00:42:21,593
That's right.

533
00:42:22,135 --> 00:42:23,220
You can do it.

534
00:42:28,141 --> 00:42:29,476
I got you.

535
00:42:35,148 --> 00:42:36,650
What's all this?

536
00:42:42,489 --> 00:42:43,657
You stand back and...

537
00:42:43,991 --> 00:42:45,409
...don't move an inch!

538
00:42:47,744 --> 00:42:48,871
Fetch the Master at Arms.

539
00:42:51,498 --> 00:42:53,083
This is completely unacceptable!

540
00:42:53,167 --> 00:42:56,003
What made you think that you could
put your hands on my fiancée?!

541
00:42:57,671 --> 00:42:58,839
Look at me, you filth!

542
00:42:59,173 --> 00:43:00,174
Cal.

543
00:43:00,340 --> 00:43:01,466
What do you think
you were doing?

544
00:43:01,675 --> 00:43:04,178
Cal, stop.
It was an accident.

545
00:43:04,845 --> 00:43:06,513
An accident?

546
00:43:06,847 --> 00:43:08,182
It was.

547
00:43:09,183 --> 00:43:10,350
Stupid, really.

548
00:43:11,185 --> 00:43:13,687
I was leaning over and I slipped.

549
00:43:16,190 --> 00:43:19,693
I was leaning far over
to see the, uh...

550
00:43:20,027 --> 00:43:22,362
...uh, uh, the uh...

551
00:43:23,197 --> 00:43:25,532
- Propellers?
- Propellers, and I slipped.

552
00:43:25,866 --> 00:43:28,535
And I would have gone
overboard but Mr. Dawson here...

553
00:43:28,869 --> 00:43:32,039
...saved me. And almost
went over himself.

554
00:43:32,956 --> 00:43:34,041
You wanted to see the...
She wanted to see the propellers.

555
00:43:34,374 --> 00:43:37,544
Like I said, women and
machinery do not mix.

556
00:43:38,378 --> 00:43:40,380
Was that the way of it?

557
00:43:42,883 --> 00:43:44,885
Yeah. Yeah, that
was pretty much it.

558
00:43:45,219 --> 00:43:46,720
Well, the boy's a hero then.

559
00:43:47,387 --> 00:43:48,639
Good for you, son.
Well done.

560
00:43:48,889 --> 00:43:50,891
So, it's all's well and back
to our brandy, eh?

561
00:43:53,560 --> 00:43:56,897
Look at you. You must be freezing.
Let's get you inside.

562
00:43:57,564 --> 00:43:59,900
Perhaps a little something
for the boy?

563
00:44:02,069 --> 00:44:03,403
Of course.

564
00:44:03,695 --> 00:44:07,241
Mr. Lovejoy,
I think a 20 should do it.

565
00:44:07,908 --> 00:44:10,577
Is that the going rate
for saving the woman you love?

566
00:44:12,246 --> 00:44:14,081
Rose is displeased.

567
00:44:14,581 --> 00:44:16,250
What to do?

568
00:44:16,708 --> 00:44:17,709
I know.

569
00:44:19,920 --> 00:44:23,590
Perhaps you could join us for
dinner tomorrow evening...

570
00:44:23,924 --> 00:44:25,425
...to regale our group...

571
00:44:25,759 --> 00:44:27,928
...with your heroic tale.

572
00:44:30,264 --> 00:44:32,432
Sure.
Count me in.

573
00:44:32,766 --> 00:44:35,102
Good.
It's settled then.

574
00:44:36,103 --> 00:44:37,437
This should be interesting.

575
00:44:46,780 --> 00:44:49,449
Can I bum a smoke?

576
00:44:58,292 --> 00:44:59,459
You'll want to tie those.

577
00:45:02,129 --> 00:45:03,213
It's interesting...

578
00:45:03,797 --> 00:45:05,549
...the young lady slipped
so suddenly...

579
00:45:05,757 --> 00:45:09,136
...and you still had time to remove
your jacket and your shoes.

580
00:45:25,319 --> 00:45:27,321
I know you've been melancholy.

581
00:45:28,322 --> 00:45:30,324
I don't pretend to know why.

582
00:45:32,993 --> 00:45:35,162
I intended to save this...

583
00:45:35,662 --> 00:45:40,334
...until the engagement
gala next week...

584
00:45:41,668 --> 00:45:44,004
...but, I thought...

585
00:45:44,338 --> 00:45:45,672
...tonight.

586
00:45:47,132 --> 00:45:48,342
Good gracious.

587
00:45:49,259 --> 00:45:52,012
Perhaps as a reminder
of my feelings for you.

588
00:45:52,846 --> 00:45:54,139
- Is it a...
- Diamond. Yes.

589
00:45:56,683 --> 00:45:59,853
56 carats to be exact.

590
00:46:01,855 --> 00:46:04,191
It was worn by Louis XVI.

591
00:46:05,025 --> 00:46:07,361
And they called
it Le Coeur de la Mer.

592
00:46:07,861 --> 00:46:09,696
- The Heart of the Ocean.
- The Heart of the Ocean. Yes.

593
00:46:16,203 --> 00:46:17,871
It's overwhelming.

594
00:46:18,330 --> 00:46:19,998
Well, it's for royalty.

595
00:46:21,208 --> 00:46:23,377
We are royalty, Rose.

596
00:46:27,381 --> 00:46:29,716
You know, there's
nothing I couldn't give you.

597
00:46:30,551 --> 00:46:32,553
There's nothing I'd deny you...

598
00:46:33,220 --> 00:46:35,389
...if you would not deny me.

599
00:46:39,560 --> 00:46:41,895
Open your heart to me, Rose.

600
00:46:57,411 --> 00:47:01,290
Well, I've been on my own since
I was 15, since my folks died.

601
00:47:02,416 --> 00:47:06,420
And I had no brothers or sisters or
close kin in that part of the country...

602
00:47:06,879 --> 00:47:10,215
...so I lit on out of there and I
haven't been back since.

603
00:47:10,424 --> 00:47:12,593
You could just call me a
tumbleweed blowing in the wind.

604
00:47:15,095 --> 00:47:19,266
Well, Rose, we've walked about a mile
around this boat deck and...

605
00:47:19,558 --> 00:47:22,561
...chewed over how great the weather's
been and how I grew up...

606
00:47:22,769 --> 00:47:26,440
...but I reckon that's not why
you came to talk to me, is it?

607
00:47:28,442 --> 00:47:30,444
- Mr. Dawson, I...
- Jack.

608
00:47:31,862 --> 00:47:32,863
Jack.

609
00:47:33,280 --> 00:47:36,533
I want to thank you
for what you did.

610
00:47:36,617 --> 00:47:41,288
Not just for pulling me back,
but for your discretion.

611
00:47:41,622 --> 00:47:42,956
You're welcome.

612
00:47:43,457 --> 00:47:44,458
Look.

613
00:47:45,542 --> 00:47:48,212
I know what you
must be thinking.

614
00:47:48,462 --> 00:47:50,088
Poor little rich girl.

615
00:47:50,255 --> 00:47:52,382
What does she know about misery?

616
00:47:52,633 --> 00:47:53,634
No.

617
00:47:54,635 --> 00:47:56,803
No, that's not what I was thinking.

618
00:47:57,137 --> 00:47:58,388
What I was thinking was...

619
00:47:58,555 --> 00:48:01,975
...what could have happened to this girl
to make her think she had no way out?

620
00:48:04,645 --> 00:48:05,646
Well I...

621
00:48:06,396 --> 00:48:10,442
It was everything.
It was my whole world and...

622
00:48:10,651 --> 00:48:11,735
...all the people in it.

623
00:48:12,402 --> 00:48:15,572
And the inertia of my life,
plunging ahead and me...

624
00:48:15,781 --> 00:48:17,616
...powerless to stop it.

625
00:48:17,825 --> 00:48:19,827
God,
look at that thing.

626
00:48:20,118 --> 00:48:22,287
You would have gone
straight to the bottom.

627
00:48:23,997 --> 00:48:26,500
500 invitations have gone out.

628
00:48:26,834 --> 00:48:29,503
All of Philadelphia society will be there.

629
00:48:29,795 --> 00:48:31,797
And all the while I feel I'm...

630
00:48:32,172 --> 00:48:34,091
...standing in the middle
of a crowded room...

631
00:48:34,174 --> 00:48:35,843
...screaming at the
top of my lungs...

632
00:48:35,968 --> 00:48:37,177
...and no one
even looks up.

633
00:48:39,012 --> 00:48:40,013
Do you love him?

634
00:48:41,348 --> 00:48:42,349
Pardon me?

635
00:48:42,683 --> 00:48:44,142
Do you love him?

636
00:48:44,685 --> 00:48:47,688
You're being very rude. You
shouldn't be asking me this.

637
00:48:48,147 --> 00:48:50,691
Well, it's a simple question.
Do you love the guy or not?

638
00:48:53,152 --> 00:48:55,195
This is not a suitable conversation.

639
00:48:55,487 --> 00:48:56,697
Why can't you just
answer the question?

640
00:48:59,366 --> 00:49:01,326
This is absurd.

641
00:49:01,952 --> 00:49:03,036
You don't know me
and I don't know you...

642
00:49:03,328 --> 00:49:06,331
...and we are not having this
conversation at all. You are rude...

643
00:49:06,540 --> 00:49:09,877
...and uncouth and presumptuous
and I am leaving now...

644
00:49:10,210 --> 00:49:13,046
...Jack. Mr. Dawson.
It's been a pleasure.

645
00:49:13,213 --> 00:49:14,965
I sought you out to thank you
and now I have thanked you.

646
00:49:15,174 --> 00:49:17,176
And you've insulted me.

647
00:49:17,384 --> 00:49:19,011
Well, you deserved it.

648
00:49:19,219 --> 00:49:20,387
- Right.
- Right.

649
00:49:23,390 --> 00:49:25,017
I thought you were leaving.

650
00:49:25,225 --> 00:49:26,560
I am.

651
00:49:28,729 --> 00:49:30,063
You are so annoying.

652
00:49:31,565 --> 00:49:32,566
Wait.

653
00:49:32,816 --> 00:49:37,070
I don't have to leave. This is
my part of the ship. You leave.

654
00:49:37,404 --> 00:49:40,407
Well, well, well.
Now who's being rude?

655
00:49:44,244 --> 00:49:47,080
What is this stupid thing
you're carrying around?

656
00:49:48,248 --> 00:49:50,584
So, what are you,
an artist or something?

657
00:49:54,755 --> 00:49:56,590
These are rather good.

658
00:49:59,927 --> 00:50:03,096
They're very good, actually.

659
00:50:10,437 --> 00:50:12,105
Jack, this is exquisite work.

660
00:50:12,439 --> 00:50:15,108
Ah, they didn't think too
much of them in old Paree.

661
00:50:15,275 --> 00:50:16,610
Paris?

662
00:50:17,903 --> 00:50:20,572
You do get around
for a p...

663
00:50:22,282 --> 00:50:26,078
Well, a... a
person of limited means.

664
00:50:26,286 --> 00:50:28,288
Go on. A poor guy. You can say it.

665
00:50:31,625 --> 00:50:33,293
Well, well, well.

666
00:50:37,631 --> 00:50:39,258
And these were drawn from life?

667
00:50:42,803 --> 00:50:44,805
Well, that's one of the good things about Paris.

668
00:50:45,305 --> 00:50:46,723
Lots of girls are willing
to take their clothes off.

669
00:50:53,272 --> 00:50:54,648
You liked this woman.

670
00:50:55,482 --> 00:50:57,651
You used her several times.

671
00:50:58,819 --> 00:50:59,820
Well.

672
00:51:00,571 --> 00:51:02,489
She had beautiful
hands, you see?

673
00:51:04,992 --> 00:51:07,327
I think you must have
had a love affair with her.

674
00:51:07,828 --> 00:51:09,830
No, no, no.
Just with her hands.

675
00:51:10,164 --> 00:51:12,833
She was a
one-legged prostitute.

676
00:51:13,959 --> 00:51:14,960
See?

677
00:51:21,508 --> 00:51:23,510
She had a good
sense of humor though.

678
00:51:26,013 --> 00:51:27,014
Oh, and this lady...

679
00:51:28,849 --> 00:51:31,852
She used to sit at this bar every night...

680
00:51:32,019 --> 00:51:33,687
...wearing every piece
of jewelry she owned...

681
00:51:33,937 --> 00:51:36,273
...just waiting for
her long, lost love.

682
00:51:37,024 --> 00:51:39,359
We called her Madame Bijoux.

683
00:51:39,860 --> 00:51:41,695
See, her clothes are all moth-eaten.

684
00:51:43,363 --> 00:51:46,200
Well,
you have a gift, Jack.

685
00:51:46,533 --> 00:51:47,868
You do.

686
00:51:48,202 --> 00:51:49,703
You see people.

687
00:51:49,995 --> 00:51:51,538
I see you.

688
00:51:53,957 --> 00:51:55,292
And?

689
00:51:56,668 --> 00:51:58,378
You wouldn't have jumped.

690
00:52:02,716 --> 00:52:06,345
But the purpose of university
is to find a suitable husband.

691
00:52:06,553 --> 00:52:08,222
Rose has already done that.

692
00:52:08,555 --> 00:52:11,391
Look, here comes that
vulgar Brown woman.

693
00:52:11,725 --> 00:52:14,394
Quickly, get up before
she sits with us.

694
00:52:15,395 --> 00:52:18,023
Hello, girls. I was hoping
I'd catch you at tea.

695
00:52:18,232 --> 00:52:19,733
We're awfully sorry,
you missed it.

696
00:52:19,900 --> 00:52:23,320
The Countess and I were just
off to take the air on the boat deck.

697
00:52:23,529 --> 00:52:26,573
What a lovely idea.
I need to catch up on my gossip.

698
00:52:30,077 --> 00:52:31,245
Countess.

699
00:52:32,746 --> 00:52:35,582
So, you've not yet lit the
last four boilers?

700
00:52:36,083 --> 00:52:37,543
No, I don't see
the need.

701
00:52:38,377 --> 00:52:39,419
We are making excellent time.

702
00:52:40,921 --> 00:52:45,259
The press knows the size of Titanic.
Now, I want them to marvel at her speed.

703
00:52:45,551 --> 00:52:47,761
We must give them
something new to print.

704
00:52:49,763 --> 00:52:51,765
This maiden voyage
of Titanic must...

705
00:52:52,266 --> 00:52:53,851
...make headlines.

706
00:52:54,101 --> 00:52:58,105
Mr. Ismay, I would prefer
not to push the engines...

707
00:52:58,438 --> 00:53:00,941
...until they've been properly run in.

708
00:53:02,276 --> 00:53:03,569
Of course I'm just a passenger.

709
00:53:03,610 --> 00:53:06,029
I leave it to your good offices
to decide what's best.

710
00:53:06,613 --> 00:53:09,283
But what a glorious end to your final crossing...

711
00:53:09,449 --> 00:53:11,034
...if we were to get into New York
on Tuesday night...

712
00:53:11,243 --> 00:53:13,787
...and surprise them all.
Make the morning papers.

713
00:53:14,580 --> 00:53:16,582
Retire with a bang, eh, E.J.?

714
00:53:20,294 --> 00:53:21,628
Good man.

715
00:53:23,046 --> 00:53:25,549
After that, I worked
on a squid boat in Monterey...

716
00:53:25,966 --> 00:53:28,468
...then I went to Los Angeles to the...

717
00:53:28,719 --> 00:53:31,889
...Santa Monica pier
and did portraits for 10 cents each.

718
00:53:32,639 --> 00:53:34,474
Why can't I be like you?

719
00:53:34,808 --> 00:53:38,312
Just head out for the horizon
whenever I feel like it.

720
00:53:40,314 --> 00:53:43,066
Say we'll go there sometime, to that pier...

721
00:53:43,317 --> 00:53:45,486
...only if we just talk about it.

722
00:53:45,819 --> 00:53:48,655
No, we'll do it. We'll drink cheap beer.

723
00:53:48,989 --> 00:53:51,658
Ride on the roller coaster till we throw up.

724
00:53:51,992 --> 00:53:55,162
We'll ride horses on the beach, in the surf.

725
00:53:55,496 --> 00:53:59,500
But you have to do it like a real cowboy.
No sidesaddle stuff.

726
00:54:00,000 --> 00:54:02,669
You mean with one leg on each side?

727
00:54:04,004 --> 00:54:05,005
Can you show me?

728
00:54:05,255 --> 00:54:07,090
Sure, if you like.

729
00:54:08,675 --> 00:54:10,344
Teach me to ride like a man.

730
00:54:10,594 --> 00:54:11,929
Chew tobacco like a man.

731
00:54:13,514 --> 00:54:15,682
And spit like a man.

732
00:54:16,016 --> 00:54:17,768
You didn't learn in finishing school?

733
00:54:18,018 --> 00:54:19,186
No.

734
00:54:19,520 --> 00:54:21,355
Come on, I'll show you.

735
00:54:22,356 --> 00:54:23,357
I'll show you how.

736
00:54:23,607 --> 00:54:26,527
Jack! No, Jack, no. Wait.

737
00:54:27,861 --> 00:54:29,863
I couldn't possibly, Jack.

738
00:54:30,197 --> 00:54:31,865
Watch closely.

739
00:54:33,534 --> 00:54:35,369
That's disgusting.

740
00:54:35,536 --> 00:54:36,537
Your turn.

741
00:54:38,872 --> 00:54:41,875
That was pitiful.
You really have to hawk it back.

742
00:54:42,209 --> 00:54:45,212
Get some leverage.
Use your arms. Arc your neck.

743
00:54:46,547 --> 00:54:48,549
You see the range on that thing?

744
00:54:49,383 --> 00:54:50,551
Okay, go.

745
00:54:54,054 --> 00:54:59,059
That was better. You have to work on it.
Really try to hawk it up.

746
00:55:06,984 --> 00:55:08,318
Mother.

747
00:55:13,740 --> 00:55:16,076
May I introduce Jack Dawson?

748
00:55:17,244 --> 00:55:19,079
Charmed, I'm sure.

749
00:55:23,750 --> 00:55:28,422
The others were gracious and curious
about the man who'd saved my life.

750
00:55:29,590 --> 00:55:32,593
But my mother looked at him like an insect.

751
00:55:33,093 --> 00:55:37,097
A dangerous insect
which must be squashed quickly.

752
00:55:37,431 --> 00:55:41,268
Sounds like you're a good man
to have around in a sticky spot.

753
00:55:44,271 --> 00:55:48,942
Why do they always insist on announcing
dinner like a damn cavalry charge?

754
00:55:49,276 --> 00:55:50,944
Shall we go dress, Mother?

755
00:55:51,945 --> 00:55:53,780
See you at dinner, Jack.

756
00:55:55,782 --> 00:55:56,783
Uh, son?

757
00:55:57,284 --> 00:55:58,452
Son!

758
00:55:58,952 --> 00:56:01,288
Do you have any idea what you're doing?

759
00:56:02,289 --> 00:56:03,290
Not really.

760
00:56:03,624 --> 00:56:06,126
You're about to go into the snake pit.

761
00:56:08,545 --> 00:56:10,214
What are you going to wear?

762
00:56:13,300 --> 00:56:15,302
I figured. Come on.

763
00:56:17,971 --> 00:56:22,309
I was right. You and my son
are just about the same size.

764
00:56:22,643 --> 00:56:24,311
Pretty close.

765
00:56:27,981 --> 00:56:30,317
You shine up like a new penny.

766
00:56:42,162 --> 00:56:43,831
Good evening, sir.

767
00:57:48,145 --> 00:57:50,898
Thousands of tons of Hockley steel
are in this ship.

768
00:57:51,148 --> 00:57:53,233
- Which part?
- All the right ones.

769
00:57:53,484 --> 00:57:56,653
Then you're accountable
if there's a problem. Where's Rose?

770
00:57:56,904 --> 00:57:58,238
She'll be along.

771
00:57:58,572 --> 00:58:00,574
There is the Countess.

772
00:58:29,436 --> 00:58:32,940
I saw that in a nickelodeon
and always wanted to do it.

773
00:58:47,371 --> 00:58:48,539
Darling...

774
00:58:49,122 --> 00:58:51,291
...surely you remember Mr. Dawson.

775
00:58:54,127 --> 00:58:57,714
It's amazing.
You could almost pass for a gentleman.

776
00:58:58,966 --> 00:59:00,133
Almost.

777
00:59:00,467 --> 00:59:01,885
This is extraordinary.

778
00:59:16,483 --> 00:59:18,152
This is a remarkable voyage.

779
00:59:18,402 --> 00:59:19,820
- Mad.
- Completely lunatic.

780
00:59:21,572 --> 00:59:23,574
There's the Countess of Rothes.

781
00:59:25,659 --> 00:59:28,662
That's John Jacob Astor...

782
00:59:29,329 --> 00:59:30,998
...the richest man on board.

783
00:59:31,248 --> 00:59:35,169
His little wifey, Madeleine,
is my age and in a delicate condition.

784
00:59:36,003 --> 00:59:38,005
See how she tries to hide it.

785
00:59:38,255 --> 00:59:39,673
Quite the scandal.

786
00:59:40,174 --> 00:59:44,678
Benjamin Guggenheim and his mistress,
Madame Aubert. Mrs. Guggenheim...

787
00:59:44,928 --> 00:59:48,599
...is at home with the children, of course.
And over here...

788
00:59:48,849 --> 00:59:50,517
...Sir Cosmo and Lucile, Lady Duff-Gordon.

789
00:59:50,767 --> 00:59:54,104
She designs naughty lingerie,
among her many talents.

790
00:59:54,354 --> 00:59:56,690
Very popular with the royals.

791
00:59:57,691 --> 00:59:59,526
Congratulations. She's splendid.

792
00:59:59,860 --> 01:00:01,361
Why, thank you.

793
01:00:02,196 --> 01:00:03,614
Escort a lady to dinner?

794
01:00:03,864 --> 01:00:05,365
Certainly.

795
01:00:06,700 --> 01:00:08,702
Sweet pea, sweet pea.

796
01:00:09,536 --> 01:00:10,954
Ain't nothing to it.

797
01:00:11,705 --> 01:00:16,210
They love money. Pretend like you own
a gold mine and you're in the club.

798
01:00:18,378 --> 01:00:20,047
Hey, Astor.

799
01:00:20,881 --> 01:00:23,550
Hello, Molly. Nice to see you.

800
01:00:23,800 --> 01:00:26,720
J.J., Madeleine,
I'd like you to meet Jack Dawson.

801
01:00:28,138 --> 01:00:29,473
Well, Jack...

802
01:00:29,890 --> 01:00:31,558
...are you of the Boston Dawsons?

803
01:00:32,559 --> 01:00:35,145
No, the Chippewa Falls Dawsons, actually.

804
01:00:35,395 --> 01:00:36,730
Oh, yes.

805
01:00:38,732 --> 01:00:42,736
He must have been nervous,
but he never faltered.

806
01:00:43,570 --> 01:00:45,739
They assumed he was one of them.

807
01:00:46,073 --> 01:00:49,243
Heir to a railroad fortune, perhaps.

808
01:00:49,576 --> 01:00:53,747
New money, obviously,
but still a member of the club.

809
01:00:54,414 --> 01:00:57,835
Mother, of course,
could always be counted upon.

810
01:00:58,418 --> 01:01:03,340
Tell us of the accommodations in steerage,
Mr. Dawson. I hear they're quite good.

811
01:01:04,842 --> 01:01:08,011
The best I've seen, ma'am. Hardly any rats.

812
01:01:11,098 --> 01:01:13,934
Mr. Dawson is joining us from third class.

813
01:01:14,184 --> 01:01:16,520
He was of help to my fiancée last night.

814
01:01:16,770 --> 01:01:19,606
It happens Mr. Dawson is quite a fine artist.

815
01:01:19,940 --> 01:01:22,442
He showed me some of his work today.

816
01:01:22,943 --> 01:01:27,781
Rose and I differ in our definition of fine art.
Not to impugn your work, sir.

817
01:01:38,625 --> 01:01:39,626
Are all these mine?

818
01:01:39,877 --> 01:01:41,962
Start from the outside and work in.

819
01:01:42,212 --> 01:01:44,214
He knows every rivet in her.

820
01:01:44,464 --> 01:01:46,800
Your ship is a wonder, Mr. Andrews.

821
01:01:47,050 --> 01:01:48,385
Thank you, Rose.

822
01:01:51,555 --> 01:01:53,140
How do you take your caviar, sir?

823
01:01:53,390 --> 01:01:56,643
No caviar for me, thanks.
Never did like it much.

824
01:01:58,479 --> 01:02:01,148
Where exactly do you live, Mr. Dawson?

825
01:02:01,565 --> 01:02:04,568
Right now, my address is the RMS Titanic.

826
01:02:04,818 --> 01:02:06,820
After that, I'm on God's good humor.

827
01:02:07,321 --> 01:02:09,239
How do you have means to travel?

828
01:02:10,157 --> 01:02:14,328
I work my way from place to place.
Tramp steamers and such.

829
01:02:14,661 --> 01:02:18,332
I won my ticket on Titanic
at a lucky hand at poker.

830
01:02:18,582 --> 01:02:20,083
A very lucky hand.

831
01:02:21,001 --> 01:02:23,003
All life is a game of luck.

832
01:02:24,171 --> 01:02:27,090
A real man makes his own luck.
Right, Dawson?

833
01:02:28,759 --> 01:02:32,596
And you find
that sort of rootless existence appealing?

834
01:02:35,682 --> 01:02:37,267
Yes, ma'am, I do.

835
01:02:38,018 --> 01:02:41,021
I've got everything I need
right here with me.

836
01:02:41,271 --> 01:02:44,107
I have air in my lungs
and blank sheets of paper.

837
01:02:45,526 --> 01:02:49,947
I love waking up, not knowing
what will happen or who I'll meet.

838
01:02:50,864 --> 01:02:52,282
Where I'll wind up.

839
01:02:52,699 --> 01:02:54,952
One night I'm sleeping under a bridge...

840
01:02:55,202 --> 01:02:59,456
...now I'm on the grandest ship
in the world, with you fine people.

841
01:02:59,706 --> 01:03:00,707
I'll take more of that.

842
01:03:02,042 --> 01:03:05,045
Life's a gift. I don't intend on wasting it.

843
01:03:06,380 --> 01:03:08,882
You never know what hand you'll get dealt.

844
01:03:09,216 --> 01:03:11,885
You take life as it comes at you. Here, Cal.

845
01:03:14,471 --> 01:03:16,139
Make each day count.

846
01:03:16,974 --> 01:03:17,975
Well said, Jack.

847
01:03:18,225 --> 01:03:19,309
Hear, hear.

848
01:03:20,310 --> 01:03:21,895
To making it count.

849
01:03:23,564 --> 01:03:25,232
To making it count.

850
01:03:25,732 --> 01:03:26,733
Bravo.

851
01:03:33,657 --> 01:03:37,411
But Mr. Brown didn't know
I'd hidden the money in the stove.

852
01:03:38,745 --> 01:03:42,749
He comes home drunk as a pig celebrating
and lights a fire.

853
01:03:46,253 --> 01:03:48,422
Next is brandy in the smoking room.

854
01:03:50,591 --> 01:03:52,676
Join me in a brandy, gentlemen?

855
01:03:54,595 --> 01:03:59,016
Now they retreat to congratulate each
other on being masters of the universe.

856
01:03:59,266 --> 01:04:01,268
Ladies, thank you for your company.

857
01:04:02,352 --> 01:04:04,021
May I escort you to the cabin?

858
01:04:04,271 --> 01:04:05,272
No, I'll stay here.

859
01:04:06,106 --> 01:04:07,107
Here, Molly.

860
01:04:08,108 --> 01:04:10,110
Joining us, Dawson?

861
01:04:10,444 --> 01:04:12,779
You don't want to stay with the women.

862
01:04:13,280 --> 01:04:15,616
No, thanks. I have to head back.

863
01:04:15,949 --> 01:04:20,621
That's best. It'll be all business and politics.
Wouldn't interest you.

864
01:04:21,705 --> 01:04:24,374
But Dawson, good of you to come.

865
01:04:29,963 --> 01:04:31,298
Must you go?

866
01:04:31,548 --> 01:04:33,884
Time for me to row with the other slaves.

867
01:04:37,471 --> 01:04:38,805
Good night, Rose.

868
01:05:18,846 --> 01:05:21,348
Want to go to a real party?

869
01:05:31,775 --> 01:05:33,944
Is okay I put my hand here?

870
01:05:53,547 --> 01:05:55,549
I can't understand you.

871
01:06:27,831 --> 01:06:30,167
I'm going to dance with her now.

872
01:06:30,334 --> 01:06:31,335
Come on.

873
01:06:31,919 --> 01:06:33,921
Come on. Come with me.

874
01:06:34,254 --> 01:06:36,089
Jack. Jack, wait.

875
01:06:38,425 --> 01:06:39,426
I can't do this.

876
01:06:39,676 --> 01:06:41,512
We'll have to get a bit closer.

877
01:06:41,762 --> 01:06:42,930
Like this.

878
01:06:46,266 --> 01:06:47,935
You're still my best girl, Cora.

879
01:06:51,188 --> 01:06:54,358
- I don't know the steps.
- Me, either. Just go with it.

880
01:06:54,775 --> 01:06:56,193
Don't think.

881
01:07:15,295 --> 01:07:17,965
Wait! Jack! Wait! Stop, Jack!

882
01:07:27,808 --> 01:07:29,309
What? Wait!

883
01:08:10,517 --> 01:08:12,186
Jack, no.

884
01:08:18,025 --> 01:08:21,695
...beyond the jurisdiction
of the Sherman Act.

885
01:08:22,029 --> 01:08:25,782
That's what Rockefeller said...
Supreme Court didn't swallow it.

886
01:08:46,053 --> 01:08:49,723
What? You think
a first-class girl can't drink?

887
01:08:51,975 --> 01:08:52,976
Get out of here.

888
01:08:53,560 --> 01:08:54,895
Are you all right?

889
01:08:56,897 --> 01:08:57,898
I'm fine.

890
01:08:58,148 --> 01:09:00,150
Two out of three.

891
01:09:01,068 --> 01:09:02,402
So...

892
01:09:03,570 --> 01:09:05,572
...you think you're tough?

893
01:09:06,907 --> 01:09:08,408
Let's see you do this.

894
01:09:10,744 --> 01:09:13,413
Hold this for me, Jack. Hold it up.

895
01:09:31,098 --> 01:09:32,182
Jesus!

896
01:09:32,432 --> 01:09:33,600
You okay?

897
01:09:33,851 --> 01:09:35,435
I haven't done that in years.

898
01:09:43,527 --> 01:09:46,280
Come on, lads. Give it all you got. Let's go.

899
01:10:12,306 --> 01:10:13,640
Coffee, sir?

900
01:10:23,567 --> 01:10:25,235
You didn't come to me last night.

901
01:10:27,488 --> 01:10:28,989
I was tired.

902
01:10:31,492 --> 01:10:34,161
Your exertions below deck
were no doubt exhausting.

903
01:10:37,331 --> 01:10:40,834
I see you had
that undertaker of a manservant follow me.

904
01:10:41,168 --> 01:10:44,087
You will never behave like that again.

905
01:10:47,674 --> 01:10:50,677
I'm not one of your mill foremen
who you can command.

906
01:10:52,179 --> 01:10:53,847
I'm your fiancée.

907
01:10:55,516 --> 01:10:57,518
My fiancée. My fiancée!

908
01:10:57,851 --> 01:10:59,853
Yes, you are! And my wife!

909
01:11:01,188 --> 01:11:05,692
My wife in practice,
if not yet by law, so you will honor me!

910
01:11:06,026 --> 01:11:08,779
You will honor me the way
a wife honors her husband.

911
01:11:09,029 --> 01:11:11,281
Because I will not be made a fool of.

912
01:11:12,115 --> 01:11:13,951
Is this in any way unclear?

913
01:11:14,868 --> 01:11:16,036
No.

914
01:11:16,370 --> 01:11:18,705
Good. Excuse me.

915
01:11:24,378 --> 01:11:26,046
Oh, Miss Rose.

916
01:11:27,714 --> 01:11:29,299
We had a little accident.

917
01:11:29,550 --> 01:11:31,718
- That's all right.
- I'm sorry.

918
01:11:32,135 --> 01:11:33,136
Let me help you.

919
01:11:33,387 --> 01:11:35,055
It's all right, miss.

920
01:11:41,562 --> 01:11:42,980
It's all right, miss.

921
01:11:48,569 --> 01:11:49,903
Tea, Trudy.

922
01:12:07,421 --> 01:12:10,591
You're not to see that boy again.
You understand?

923
01:12:11,925 --> 01:12:14,261
Rose, I forbid it.

924
01:12:15,262 --> 01:12:18,265
Stop it, Mother.
You'll give yourself a nosebleed.

925
01:12:18,599 --> 01:12:20,267
This is not a game.

926
01:12:20,851 --> 01:12:24,438
Our situation is precarious.
You know the money's gone.

927
01:12:24,771 --> 01:12:29,109
Of course I know.
You remind me every day.

928
01:12:30,194 --> 01:12:35,032
Your father left us nothing but a legacy
of bad debts hidden by a good name.

929
01:12:35,282 --> 01:12:37,951
That name is the only card we have to play.

930
01:12:38,619 --> 01:12:40,287
I don't understand you.

931
01:12:40,954 --> 01:12:44,958
It is a fine match with Hockley.
It will ensure our survival.

932
01:12:46,293 --> 01:12:47,961
How can you put this on me?

933
01:12:48,212 --> 01:12:49,713
Why are you being so selfish?

934
01:12:50,214 --> 01:12:52,049
I'm being selfish?

935
01:12:55,552 --> 01:12:58,472
Do you want to see me
working as a seamstress?

936
01:13:00,307 --> 01:13:02,142
Is that what you want?

937
01:13:04,812 --> 01:13:07,648
To see our fine things sold at auction?

938
01:13:09,316 --> 01:13:11,151
Our memories scattered?

939
01:13:22,329 --> 01:13:23,997
It's so unfair.

940
01:13:25,332 --> 01:13:27,167
Of course it's unfair.

941
01:13:28,502 --> 01:13:29,837
We're women.

942
01:13:32,339 --> 01:13:34,508
Our choices are never easy.

943
01:13:56,363 --> 01:14:00,200
Protect them by Thy guiding hand

944
01:14:00,534 --> 01:14:05,372
From every peril on the land

945
01:14:07,374 --> 01:14:11,378
O, spirit whom the Father sent

946
01:14:12,045 --> 01:14:16,216
To spread abroad the firmament

947
01:14:16,550 --> 01:14:20,888
O, wind of heaven, by Thy might

948
01:14:21,221 --> 01:14:26,059
Save all who dare the eagle's flight

949
01:14:26,393 --> 01:14:30,230
And keep them by Thy watchful care...

950
01:14:32,900 --> 01:14:34,568
Hello, Mr. Andrews.

951
01:14:44,828 --> 01:14:46,246
I need to talk to someone.

952
01:14:46,497 --> 01:14:48,749
You're not supposed to be in here.

953
01:14:53,420 --> 01:14:55,005
I was here last night, remember?

954
01:14:55,255 --> 01:14:56,924
No. Now please turn around.

955
01:14:57,174 --> 01:15:00,010
He'll tell you. I just need to talk...

956
01:15:00,260 --> 01:15:03,430
Mr. Hockley and Mrs. DeWitt Bukater...

957
01:15:03,764 --> 01:15:06,600
...are still appreciative of your assistance.

958
01:15:06,934 --> 01:15:10,437
They asked me
to give you this in gratitude...

959
01:15:10,687 --> 01:15:12,272
I don't want your money.

960
01:15:12,606 --> 01:15:16,443
...and remind you you are
in third class and your presence here...

961
01:15:16,693 --> 01:15:18,445
...is no longer appropriate.

962
01:15:18,695 --> 01:15:20,030
Let me speak to Rose.

963
01:15:20,280 --> 01:15:24,284
Gentlemen, please see Mr. Dawson
returns to where he belongs...

964
01:15:24,618 --> 01:15:26,286
...and that he stays there?

965
01:15:27,120 --> 01:15:28,121
Yes, sir.

966
01:15:28,372 --> 01:15:29,540
Come along, you.

967
01:15:31,625 --> 01:15:34,795
Hear us when we cry to Thee

968
01:15:35,128 --> 01:15:39,633
For those in peril on the sea

969
01:15:40,634 --> 01:15:42,469
Why are there two steering wheels?

970
01:15:42,719 --> 01:15:44,221
We use this one near shore.

971
01:15:44,471 --> 01:15:48,142
Excuse me, sir.
Another ice warning, from the Noordam.

972
01:15:48,392 --> 01:15:49,726
Thank you, Sparks.

973
01:15:51,979 --> 01:15:55,315
Not to worry.
Quite normal for this time of year.

974
01:15:56,316 --> 01:16:00,320
In fact, we're speeding up.
I've ordered the last boilers lit.

975
01:16:04,366 --> 01:16:07,327
Okay, son, wind it up tight
like I showed you. That's right.

976
01:16:07,536 --> 01:16:09,163
Okay, now let it go.

977
01:16:12,207 --> 01:16:14,209
- It was good, wasn't it?
- Quite nice. That's excellent.

978
01:16:21,216 --> 01:16:24,219
Mr. Andrews... Forgive me.

979
01:16:24,845 --> 01:16:26,263
I did the sum
in my head...

980
01:16:26,889 --> 01:16:30,392
...and with the number of lifeboats
times the capacity you mentioned...

981
01:16:30,726 --> 01:16:34,229
Forgive me, but it seems that there are
not enough for everyone aboard.

982
01:16:35,022 --> 01:16:36,732
About half, actually.

983
01:16:37,566 --> 01:16:39,067
Rose, you miss nothing,
do you?

984
01:16:39,902 --> 01:16:42,070
In fact, I put in these new
type davits...

985
01:16:42,404 --> 01:16:45,032
...which can take an extra row
of boats inside this one.

986
01:16:45,741 --> 01:16:47,701
But it was thought,
by some...

987
01:16:47,868 --> 01:16:49,453
...the deck would look
too cluttered.

988
01:16:49,912 --> 01:16:52,247
So, I was overruled.

989
01:16:52,748 --> 01:16:55,751
It's a waste of deck space
as it is on an unsinkable ship.

990
01:16:56,084 --> 01:16:57,753
Sleep soundly, young Rose.

991
01:16:57,878 --> 01:17:00,464
I have built you a good ship,
strong and true.

992
01:17:00,756 --> 01:17:02,424
She's all the lifeboat
you need.

993
01:17:02,758 --> 01:17:05,761
Just keep heading aft. The next
stop will be the engine room.

994
01:17:11,099 --> 01:17:15,437
Jack, this is impossible.
I can't see you.

995
01:17:15,729 --> 01:17:18,607
- I need to talk to you.
- No, Jack. No.

996
01:17:20,108 --> 01:17:22,444
Jack.
I'm engaged.

997
01:17:23,445 --> 01:17:25,280
I'm marrying Cal.

998
01:17:26,114 --> 01:17:27,241
I love Cal.

999
01:17:29,785 --> 01:17:31,119
Rose...

1000
01:17:31,620 --> 01:17:36,124
...you're no picnic. All right?
You're a spoiled little brat even.

1001
01:17:36,458 --> 01:17:40,963
But under that, you're the
most amazingly, astounding...

1002
01:17:41,296 --> 01:17:42,965
...wonderful girl...

1003
01:17:43,590 --> 01:17:45,425
...woman, that I've ever known.

1004
01:17:45,509 --> 01:17:46,593
Jack, I...

1005
01:17:46,635 --> 01:17:49,346
No, let me try and get
this out. You're ama...

1006
01:17:51,807 --> 01:17:54,810
I'm not an idiot.
I know how the world works.

1007
01:17:55,144 --> 01:17:57,020
I've got ten bucks
in my pocket.

1008
01:17:57,146 --> 01:17:59,940
I have nothing to offer
you and I know that.

1009
01:18:00,149 --> 01:18:01,817
I understand.

1010
01:18:02,776 --> 01:18:04,444
But I'm too involved now.

1011
01:18:04,820 --> 01:18:06,822
You jump, I jump.
Remember?

1012
01:18:07,156 --> 01:18:09,658
I can't turn away without
knowing you'll be all right.

1013
01:18:11,451 --> 01:18:12,452
That's all that I want.

1014
01:18:13,829 --> 01:18:15,330
Well, I'm fine.

1015
01:18:16,498 --> 01:18:19,001
I'll be fine. Really.

1016
01:18:20,002 --> 01:18:21,170
Really?

1017
01:18:23,338 --> 01:18:24,840
I don't think so.

1018
01:18:25,841 --> 01:18:27,968
They've got you trapped, Rose.

1019
01:18:28,135 --> 01:18:29,511
And you're gonna die if you
don't break free.

1020
01:18:29,636 --> 01:18:30,679
Maybe not right away...

1021
01:18:30,804 --> 01:18:32,473
...because you're strong...

1022
01:18:33,849 --> 01:18:37,186
...but sooner or later that
fire that I love about you, Rose...

1023
01:18:37,519 --> 01:18:40,022
...that fire is gonna
burn out.

1024
01:18:44,860 --> 01:18:46,653
It's not up to you
to save me, Jack.

1025
01:18:49,156 --> 01:18:50,365
You're right.

1026
01:18:51,700 --> 01:18:53,368
Only you can do that.

1027
01:18:59,374 --> 01:19:00,876
I'm going back.

1028
01:19:01,210 --> 01:19:02,711
Leave me alone.

1029
01:19:14,223 --> 01:19:17,392
Tell Lucile about the disaster
you had with the stationers.

1030
01:19:17,684 --> 01:19:20,354
Well, of course the invitations
had to be sent back, twice.

1031
01:19:20,562 --> 01:19:21,730
Oh, my dear.

1032
01:19:22,022 --> 01:19:23,565
And the dreadful
bridesmaids' gowns.

1033
01:19:23,690 --> 01:19:26,026
Let me tell you what an
odyssey that has been.

1034
01:19:26,235 --> 01:19:28,529
Rose decided she
wanted lavender.

1035
01:19:29,279 --> 01:19:30,447
She knows I detest the color.

1036
01:19:30,906 --> 01:19:32,199
So, she did it only to spite me.

1037
01:19:32,407 --> 01:19:34,409
If only you'd come to
me sooner.

1038
01:19:34,701 --> 01:19:37,538
Ruth saw some of my designs in
La Mode Illustrée.

1039
01:19:37,746 --> 01:19:41,083
They were for the trousseau of the Duchess
of Marlborough's youngest daughter.

1040
01:19:41,208 --> 01:19:42,209
They were quite charming.

1041
01:19:42,292 --> 01:19:44,294
But, I think you'll agree,
my dear, that together...

1042
01:19:44,586 --> 01:19:47,756
...we've created something
of a phoenix from the ashes.

1043
01:20:02,563 --> 01:20:03,564
Hello, Jack.

1044
01:20:09,278 --> 01:20:11,113
I changed my mind.

1045
01:20:17,077 --> 01:20:18,287
They said you might be up here.

1046
01:20:21,290 --> 01:20:22,624
Give me your hand.

1047
01:20:30,132 --> 01:20:31,467
Now close your eyes.

1048
01:20:32,801 --> 01:20:34,136
Go on.

1049
01:20:37,473 --> 01:20:38,974
Now, step up.

1050
01:20:42,811 --> 01:20:44,104
Now, hold onto the railing.

1051
01:20:44,188 --> 01:20:46,190
Keep your eyes closed.
Don't peek.

1052
01:20:46,440 --> 01:20:47,441
I'm not.

1053
01:20:48,817 --> 01:20:50,819
Now, step up onto the rail.

1054
01:20:54,823 --> 01:20:56,825
Hold on. Hold on.

1055
01:20:57,326 --> 01:20:59,161
Keep your eyes closed.

1056
01:20:59,661 --> 01:21:00,996
Do you trust me?

1057
01:21:01,497 --> 01:21:02,831
I trust you.

1058
01:21:12,674 --> 01:21:13,675
All right...

1059
01:21:14,051 --> 01:21:15,552
...open your eyes.

1060
01:21:22,643 --> 01:21:23,644
I'm flying.

1061
01:21:24,144 --> 01:21:25,145
Jack.

1062
01:21:50,254 --> 01:21:54,383
Come, Josephine, in my
flying machine. Going up...

1063
01:21:55,217 --> 01:21:58,554
...she goes. Up she goes.

1064
01:22:46,268 --> 01:22:49,271
That was the last time
Titanic ever saw daylight.

1065
01:22:50,731 --> 01:22:52,816
We're up to dusk the
night of the sinking.

1066
01:22:53,650 --> 01:22:54,902
6 hours to go.

1067
01:22:55,110 --> 01:22:58,071
Incredible. There's Smith and
he's standing there and...

1068
01:22:58,155 --> 01:22:59,823
...he's got the iceberg warning
in his fucking hand...

1069
01:23:00,073 --> 01:23:03,076
...excuse me... his hand,
and he's ordering more speed.

1070
01:23:03,285 --> 01:23:06,455
26 years of experience
working against him.

1071
01:23:06,747 --> 01:23:08,749
He figures anything big
enough to sink, the ship...

1072
01:23:08,916 --> 01:23:10,667
...they're gonna see in time to turn.

1073
01:23:10,959 --> 01:23:13,420
But the ship's too big
with too small a rudder.

1074
01:23:13,587 --> 01:23:15,631
Doesn't corner worth a damn.

1075
01:23:16,799 --> 01:23:19,134
Everything he knows
is wrong.

1076
01:23:31,814 --> 01:23:35,651
It's quite proper, I assure you.
This is the sitting room.

1077
01:23:37,653 --> 01:23:39,154
- Will this light do?
- What?

1078
01:23:40,489 --> 01:23:41,824
Don't artists need good light?

1079
01:23:42,115 --> 01:23:44,326
That is true, but I'm not
used to working in...

1080
01:23:45,118 --> 01:23:46,703
...such horrible conditions.

1081
01:23:47,496 --> 01:23:48,831
Monet!

1082
01:23:49,665 --> 01:23:52,334
- Do you know his work?
- Of course.

1083
01:23:52,835 --> 01:23:54,670
Look at his use of color here.
Isn't he great?

1084
01:23:54,962 --> 01:23:56,964
I know. It's extraordinary.

1085
01:23:59,466 --> 01:24:02,803
Cal insists on carting
this hideous thing everywhere.

1086
01:24:03,470 --> 01:24:06,140
Should we be expecting him
any time soon?

1087
01:24:06,640 --> 01:24:09,977
Not as long as the cigars
and brandy hold out.

1088
01:24:13,355 --> 01:24:14,356
That's nice.

1089
01:24:14,565 --> 01:24:16,400
What is it,
a sapphire?

1090
01:24:17,192 --> 01:24:18,318
A diamond.

1091
01:24:18,986 --> 01:24:20,404
A very rare diamond.

1092
01:24:24,199 --> 01:24:26,827
Jack, I want you to draw me
like one of your French girls.

1093
01:24:28,203 --> 01:24:29,538
Wearing this.

1094
01:24:29,872 --> 01:24:31,039
All right.

1095
01:24:32,875 --> 01:24:34,877
Wearing only this.

1096
01:25:10,287 --> 01:25:14,082
The last thing I need is another picture of me
looking like a porcelain doll.

1097
01:25:18,045 --> 01:25:19,046
As a paying customer...

1098
01:25:22,049 --> 01:25:23,926
...I expect to get
what I want.

1099
01:25:41,777 --> 01:25:44,571
Over on the bed
...uh, the couch.

1100
01:25:53,747 --> 01:25:54,748
Come. Lie down.

1101
01:25:58,252 --> 01:25:59,753
- Tell me when it looks right.
- Keep that.

1102
01:25:59,962 --> 01:26:01,797
Put your arm back
the way it was.

1103
01:26:04,466 --> 01:26:07,636
Put that other arm up,
that hand right by your face there.

1104
01:26:09,138 --> 01:26:10,139
Right.

1105
01:26:11,140 --> 01:26:13,308
Now, head down.

1106
01:26:15,936 --> 01:26:17,813
Eyes to me.
Keep them on me.

1107
01:26:19,815 --> 01:26:21,984
And try to stay still.

1108
01:26:40,502 --> 01:26:42,504
So serious.

1109
01:27:23,879 --> 01:27:26,882
I believe you are blushing,
Mr. Big Artiste.

1110
01:27:31,386 --> 01:27:34,223
I can't imagine
Monsieur Monet blushing.

1111
01:27:35,557 --> 01:27:37,226
He does landscapes.

1112
01:27:37,893 --> 01:27:40,062
- Just relax your face.
- Sorry.

1113
01:27:40,395 --> 01:27:41,730
No laughing.

1114
01:28:12,761 --> 01:28:15,764
My heart was pounding
the whole time.

1115
01:28:16,098 --> 01:28:20,102
It was the most erotic
moment of my life...

1116
01:28:23,772 --> 01:28:26,108
...up until then, at least.

1117
01:28:26,608 --> 01:28:28,402
So what happened next?

1118
01:28:29,278 --> 01:28:31,947
You mean,
did we do it?

1119
01:28:34,449 --> 01:28:36,785
Sorry to disappoint you, Mr. Bodine.

1120
01:28:37,286 --> 01:28:39,788
Jack was very professional.

1121
01:28:47,796 --> 01:28:48,964
Thank you.

1122
01:28:57,097 --> 01:28:58,432
What are you doing?

1123
01:28:59,308 --> 01:29:01,602
Will you put this
back in the safe for me?

1124
01:29:13,655 --> 01:29:15,491
Gentlemen, would you excuse me.

1125
01:29:17,826 --> 01:29:19,828
None of the stewards
have seen her.

1126
01:29:20,829 --> 01:29:23,624
This is absurd.
It's a ship.

1127
01:29:23,707 --> 01:29:25,876
There's only so many
places she could be.

1128
01:29:26,168 --> 01:29:27,836
Lovejoy, find her.

1129
01:29:45,145 --> 01:29:46,480
- Clear.
- Yes.

1130
01:29:48,190 --> 01:29:51,693
I don't think I've ever
seen such a flat calm.

1131
01:29:52,194 --> 01:29:53,195
Like a mill pond.

1132
01:29:54,363 --> 01:29:55,906
Not a breath of wind.

1133
01:29:57,032 --> 01:30:00,035
It will make the bergs
harder to see...

1134
01:30:00,369 --> 01:30:02,329
...with no breaking
water at the base.

1135
01:30:13,841 --> 01:30:14,842
Well, I'm off.

1136
01:30:14,925 --> 01:30:18,095
Maintain speed and
heading, Mr. Lightoller.

1137
01:30:18,846 --> 01:30:20,097
Yes, sir.

1138
01:30:31,400 --> 01:30:33,735
It's getting cold.
You look nice.

1139
01:30:34,069 --> 01:30:35,404
Miss Rose?

1140
01:30:35,904 --> 01:30:37,573
My drawings!

1141
01:31:03,599 --> 01:31:04,892
Come on!

1142
01:31:07,936 --> 01:31:09,271
Wait, wait, wait!

1143
01:31:09,605 --> 01:31:10,939
Wait, wait, wait!

1144
01:31:11,899 --> 01:31:13,442
- Go. Go. Down, down.
- Take us down, quickly. Quickly!

1145
01:31:21,074 --> 01:31:22,075
Bye.

1146
01:31:29,958 --> 01:31:31,293
Sorry.

1147
01:31:36,632 --> 01:31:38,300
- Keep going.
- Thank you, I've got it.

1148
01:31:48,602 --> 01:31:50,437
Pretty tough for
a valet, this fella.

1149
01:31:50,521 --> 01:31:52,272
Seems more like a cop.

1150
01:31:52,481 --> 01:31:53,607
I think he was.

1151
01:31:54,316 --> 01:31:55,943
- Oh, shit.
- Go!

1152
01:32:00,823 --> 01:32:02,324
No, over here!

1153
01:32:02,658 --> 01:32:03,826
Quick!

1154
01:32:10,332 --> 01:32:12,000
Now what?

1155
01:32:12,292 --> 01:32:13,627
What?

1156
01:32:18,841 --> 01:32:20,509
More coal for number
one, mate.

1157
01:32:20,801 --> 01:32:23,303
Hold up? What are you two
doing down here?

1158
01:32:23,846 --> 01:32:24,847
You shouldn't be down here.

1159
01:32:25,180 --> 01:32:26,223
It could be dangerous!

1160
01:32:30,644 --> 01:32:31,645
Carry on!

1161
01:32:32,020 --> 01:32:33,897
Don't mind us. You're
doing a great job!

1162
01:32:34,064 --> 01:32:35,566
Keep up the good work!

1163
01:32:51,874 --> 01:32:53,876
Look at what we have here, huh?

1164
01:33:12,060 --> 01:33:13,395
Thank you.

1165
01:33:25,073 --> 01:33:26,909
Where to, miss?

1166
01:33:28,076 --> 01:33:29,745
To the stars.

1167
01:33:48,764 --> 01:33:50,265
You nervous?

1168
01:33:52,726 --> 01:33:53,894
No.

1169
01:34:10,786 --> 01:34:12,788
Put your hands on me, Jack.

1170
01:34:36,812 --> 01:34:38,313
It's bloody cold.

1171
01:34:38,814 --> 01:34:42,317
You know, I can smell ice, you know.
When it's near.

1172
01:34:43,652 --> 01:34:44,987
Bollocks!

1173
01:34:45,320 --> 01:34:46,989
Well, I can, all right?

1174
01:34:47,322 --> 01:34:49,449
Did you ever find those
binoculars for the lookouts?

1175
01:34:49,658 --> 01:34:51,493
Haven't seen them
since Southampton.

1176
01:34:52,161 --> 01:34:53,495
Well, I'll be on
my rounds.

1177
01:34:54,454 --> 01:34:55,455
Cheerio.

1178
01:35:26,695 --> 01:35:28,030
You're trembling.

1179
01:35:30,491 --> 01:35:31,533
Don't worry.

1180
01:35:31,658 --> 01:35:33,410
I'll be all right.

1181
01:35:54,723 --> 01:35:56,558
- They ran down there.
- Right.

1182
01:36:06,318 --> 01:36:07,986
Anything missing?

1183
01:36:33,011 --> 01:36:34,847
I have a better idea.

1184
01:36:47,693 --> 01:36:48,861
Got you!

1185
01:36:58,120 --> 01:37:00,956
Did you see those guys' faces?

1186
01:37:01,540 --> 01:37:03,375
Did you see them?

1187
01:37:09,715 --> 01:37:11,550
When the ship docks...

1188
01:37:12,885 --> 01:37:14,636
...I'm getting off with you.

1189
01:37:15,721 --> 01:37:17,055
This is crazy.

1190
01:37:17,222 --> 01:37:20,058
I know. It doesn't make any sense.

1191
01:37:21,560 --> 01:37:23,061
That's why I trust it.

1192
01:37:32,070 --> 01:37:34,740
Here, look at this.

1193
01:37:35,574 --> 01:37:37,576
Look at that, would you?

1194
01:37:37,910 --> 01:37:39,411
They're warmer than we are.

1195
01:37:39,828 --> 01:37:44,166
If that's what it takes for us to get warm,
I'd rather not.

1196
01:37:56,428 --> 01:37:57,930
Bugger me!

1197
01:38:03,268 --> 01:38:04,770
Pick up, you bastards!

1198
01:38:08,440 --> 01:38:09,441
Is anyone there?!

1199
01:38:09,691 --> 01:38:10,859
What do you see?

1200
01:38:11,109 --> 01:38:12,528
Iceberg, right ahead!

1201
01:38:12,778 --> 01:38:13,862
Thank you.

1202
01:38:16,198 --> 01:38:17,199
Iceberg ahead!

1203
01:38:17,366 --> 01:38:19,368
Hard a' starboard!

1204
01:38:26,291 --> 01:38:28,544
Turn! Turn! Smartly!

1205
01:38:33,799 --> 01:38:34,800
Full astern!

1206
01:38:37,136 --> 01:38:38,137
Hard over.

1207
01:38:38,303 --> 01:38:39,972
Helm's hard over, sir.

1208
01:38:43,642 --> 01:38:45,144
Go, lads, go!

1209
01:38:47,563 --> 01:38:50,315
Bring that steam down! Bring it down!

1210
01:38:52,151 --> 01:38:54,987
Shut all the dampers! Shut them!

1211
01:38:59,825 --> 01:39:00,826
Hold it.

1212
01:39:02,661 --> 01:39:03,662
Hold it!

1213
01:39:05,080 --> 01:39:06,832
Now! Engage reversing engine!

1214
01:39:35,861 --> 01:39:37,362
Why ain't they turning?

1215
01:39:37,613 --> 01:39:38,780
Is it hard over?!

1216
01:39:39,031 --> 01:39:41,033
It is, sir. Hard over.

1217
01:39:45,037 --> 01:39:49,208
Come on, come on, come on. Turn.

1218
01:40:00,385 --> 01:40:01,720
Yes.

1219
01:40:06,892 --> 01:40:08,560
It's going to hit!

1220
01:40:19,988 --> 01:40:21,490
Jesus Christ!

1221
01:40:42,261 --> 01:40:43,428
Jesus!

1222
01:40:43,679 --> 01:40:44,680
Hard to port!

1223
01:40:44,930 --> 01:40:46,265
Hard to port!

1224
01:40:56,108 --> 01:40:57,609
Get back!

1225
01:41:27,055 --> 01:41:28,390
Let's go!

1226
01:41:28,640 --> 01:41:31,977
They're closing the doors! Get out!

1227
01:41:38,484 --> 01:41:40,819
Get out the door! Go!

1228
01:41:41,153 --> 01:41:44,156
Go! Come on, lads! Go, lads, go!

1229
01:41:53,832 --> 01:41:55,501
Go! Go!

1230
01:41:56,001 --> 01:41:58,003
Out! Out!

1231
01:42:12,684 --> 01:42:14,353
Oh, my God.

1232
01:42:15,187 --> 01:42:16,522
That was a close shave.

1233
01:42:16,855 --> 01:42:19,775
Smell ice, can you? Bleedin' Christ!

1234
01:42:23,862 --> 01:42:26,698
Note the time. Enter it in the log.

1235
01:42:32,454 --> 01:42:34,122
What was that, Mr. Murdoch?

1236
01:42:35,040 --> 01:42:36,458
An iceberg, sir.

1237
01:42:37,543 --> 01:42:41,046
I put her hard to starboard, but it was too close.

1238
01:42:41,380 --> 01:42:43,549
I tried to port round it, but...

1239
01:42:43,882 --> 01:42:47,052
- Close the watertight doors.
- They're closed, sir.

1240
01:42:50,222 --> 01:42:51,390
All stop.

1241
01:43:00,732 --> 01:43:02,901
Have the carpenter sound the ship.

1242
01:43:14,580 --> 01:43:17,916
Come on, let's get the hell out of here!

1243
01:43:22,754 --> 01:43:25,591
Why have the engines stopped? I felt a shudder.

1244
01:43:25,841 --> 01:43:28,510
Not to worry. We threw a propeller blade.

1245
01:43:28,760 --> 01:43:31,597
That's the shudder you felt.
Do you need anything?

1246
01:43:32,431 --> 01:43:33,515
No, thank you.

1247
01:43:38,437 --> 01:43:40,939
There's talk of an iceberg.

1248
01:43:41,190 --> 01:43:42,941
I don't see anything. Do you?

1249
01:43:45,110 --> 01:43:48,280
If this is where the rats are going, I am, too.

1250
01:43:55,287 --> 01:43:56,955
- You.
- There is no emergency.

1251
01:43:57,206 --> 01:44:00,042
- There is. I've been robbed.
- Get the Master at Arms.

1252
01:44:00,626 --> 01:44:02,294
Now, you moron!

1253
01:44:06,965 --> 01:44:08,300
Did I miss the fun?

1254
01:44:09,468 --> 01:44:13,138
- Did you see what happened?
- No. I guess it hit over there.

1255
01:44:14,306 --> 01:44:18,560
Boiler room six is flooded eight feet
and the mail hold is worse.

1256
01:44:18,811 --> 01:44:21,230
- Can you shore up?
- Not unless the pumps get ahead.

1257
01:44:21,480 --> 01:44:24,650
- Have you seen the mail hold?
- It's already underwater.

1258
01:44:25,234 --> 01:44:26,902
This is bad.

1259
01:44:29,238 --> 01:44:30,823
We should tell Mother and Cal.

1260
01:44:31,907 --> 01:44:33,992
I think they're very good, sir.

1261
01:44:36,829 --> 01:44:39,832
Don't touch anything.
I want the room photographed.

1262
01:44:44,837 --> 01:44:47,005
We've been looking for you, miss.

1263
01:44:51,844 --> 01:44:52,928
Here we go.

1264
01:44:58,851 --> 01:45:00,269
Something serious has happened.

1265
01:45:01,854 --> 01:45:03,355
Yes, it has.

1266
01:45:04,857 --> 01:45:08,277
Indeed.
Two things dear to me have disappeared.

1267
01:45:08,527 --> 01:45:12,698
Now that one is back,
I know where to find the other. Search him.

1268
01:45:12,948 --> 01:45:14,783
- Take your coat off.
- Now what?

1269
01:45:15,951 --> 01:45:19,955
What are you doing?
We're in the middle of an emergency.

1270
01:45:20,205 --> 01:45:22,291
- Is this it?
- That's it.

1271
01:45:22,875 --> 01:45:24,710
This is horseshit!

1272
01:45:26,044 --> 01:45:27,379
Don't you believe it.

1273
01:45:27,713 --> 01:45:31,049
- He couldn't have.
- Easy enough for a professional.

1274
01:45:31,300 --> 01:45:33,802
I was with him the entire time.

1275
01:45:34,052 --> 01:45:37,055
Perhaps he did it while you were putting
your clothes back on, dear.

1276
01:45:38,724 --> 01:45:40,976
Real slick. They put it in my pocket.

1277
01:45:41,226 --> 01:45:44,062
- Shut up.
- It isn't even your pocket.

1278
01:45:44,313 --> 01:45:45,814
"Property of A.L. Ryerson."

1279
01:45:50,152 --> 01:45:51,653
That was reported stolen.

1280
01:45:51,904 --> 01:45:53,489
I just borrowed it.

1281
01:45:53,739 --> 01:45:56,074
Oh, we have an honest thief.

1282
01:45:56,408 --> 01:45:58,577
You know I didn't do this, Rose.

1283
01:45:59,411 --> 01:46:01,413
Don't believe them. You know it.

1284
01:46:01,663 --> 01:46:02,664
Let's go, son.

1285
01:46:02,915 --> 01:46:04,750
You know I didn't do it!

1286
01:46:05,083 --> 01:46:08,086
There's a good lad. Come on.

1287
01:46:08,420 --> 01:46:10,756
You know I didn't do it! You know me!

1288
01:46:12,674 --> 01:46:14,927
This is most unfortunate, Captain.

1289
01:46:18,430 --> 01:46:21,850
Water fourteen feet above the keel
in ten minutes...

1290
01:46:22,100 --> 01:46:25,437
...in the forepeak,
all three holds and boiler room six.

1291
01:46:25,687 --> 01:46:26,688
That's right.

1292
01:46:26,939 --> 01:46:28,273
When can we get underway?

1293
01:46:28,524 --> 01:46:30,526
That's five compartments.

1294
01:46:32,444 --> 01:46:36,448
She can float with four compartments breached,
but not five.

1295
01:46:37,115 --> 01:46:40,786
Not five. As she goes down,
the water will spill...

1296
01:46:41,036 --> 01:46:45,207
...over the tops of the bulkheads at E deck,
one to the next...

1297
01:46:45,457 --> 01:46:48,127
...back and back. There's no stopping it.

1298
01:46:48,460 --> 01:46:49,711
The pumps.

1299
01:46:49,962 --> 01:46:53,132
The pumps buy you time, but minutes only.

1300
01:46:53,799 --> 01:46:56,051
As of now, no matter what we do...

1301
01:46:56,969 --> 01:46:59,138
...Titanic will founder.

1302
01:47:01,473 --> 01:47:02,808
But this ship can't sink.

1303
01:47:03,058 --> 01:47:05,894
She's made of iron. I assure you, she can.

1304
01:47:06,478 --> 01:47:07,479
And she will.

1305
01:47:08,313 --> 01:47:10,399
It's a mathematical certainty.

1306
01:47:14,820 --> 01:47:16,321
How much time?

1307
01:47:23,829 --> 01:47:26,331
An hour. Two, at most.

1308
01:47:32,337 --> 01:47:34,423
How many aboard, Mr. Murdoch?

1309
01:47:34,840 --> 01:47:37,676
Two thousand, two hundred souls, sir.

1310
01:47:44,349 --> 01:47:47,853
Well, I believe you may get your headlines,
Mr. Ismay.

1311
01:48:05,370 --> 01:48:07,539
Oh, it is a little slut, isn't it?

1312
01:48:08,373 --> 01:48:10,542
Look at me when I'm talking to you!

1313
01:48:10,793 --> 01:48:12,961
- Mr. Hockley?
- Not now. We're busy.

1314
01:48:13,212 --> 01:48:16,632
You've been asked to put on lifebelts
and go to the boat deck.

1315
01:48:16,882 --> 01:48:17,883
I said, not now.

1316
01:48:18,133 --> 01:48:23,138
I'm sorry, Mr. Hockley, but it's Captain's orders.
Dress warmly.

1317
01:48:23,388 --> 01:48:25,557
It's quite cold out.

1318
01:48:25,891 --> 01:48:28,727
May I suggest topcoats and hats?

1319
01:48:29,061 --> 01:48:30,896
This is ridiculous.

1320
01:48:31,563 --> 01:48:35,234
Not to worry, miss.
I'm sure it's just a precaution.

1321
01:48:35,567 --> 01:48:37,569
Everybody up! Lifebelts on!

1322
01:48:39,238 --> 01:48:40,823
What's he on about?

1323
01:48:41,740 --> 01:48:43,575
- Put your lifebelts on!
- What is it?

1324
01:48:43,826 --> 01:48:45,160
Just put them on.

1325
01:48:46,411 --> 01:48:47,579
C.Q.D.?

1326
01:48:48,247 --> 01:48:49,414
Sir?

1327
01:48:51,083 --> 01:48:54,920
That's right, C.Q.D. The distress call.
That's our position.

1328
01:49:00,509 --> 01:49:04,763
Tell whoever responds we're going down
and need immediate assistance.

1329
01:49:14,273 --> 01:49:15,607
Blimey.

1330
01:49:25,784 --> 01:49:27,619
Keep lowering!

1331
01:49:27,953 --> 01:49:29,955
Keep lowering!

1332
01:49:33,792 --> 01:49:37,629
Steady! Make it taut! And winch out!

1333
01:49:41,467 --> 01:49:45,471
Uncover this boat! Uncover all the boats aft!

1334
01:49:45,804 --> 01:49:47,473
Release those ties!

1335
01:49:47,806 --> 01:49:50,559
Roll back that cover! Smartly now!

1336
01:49:51,143 --> 01:49:52,644
Where are the passengers?

1337
01:49:52,895 --> 01:49:56,231
They went inside. Too cold and noisy for them.

1338
01:49:56,482 --> 01:50:00,819
You there! Get down here
and help with these lines!

1339
01:50:15,000 --> 01:50:16,835
Care for a drink, sir?

1340
01:50:19,338 --> 01:50:24,259
Sonny, what's doing? You get us all trussed up
and now we're cooling our heels.

1341
01:50:24,510 --> 01:50:27,012
Sorry, ma'am. Let me go find out.

1342
01:50:27,679 --> 01:50:30,015
Nobody knows what's going on.

1343
01:50:30,265 --> 01:50:33,185
Just like the damn English... everything by the book.

1344
01:50:33,435 --> 01:50:36,188
No need for language, Mr. Hockley.

1345
01:50:36,355 --> 01:50:41,193
Go back and turn on the heaters in our rooms.
I want a cup of tea when I return.

1346
01:50:52,037 --> 01:50:53,038
Mr. Andrews.

1347
01:50:55,040 --> 01:50:58,377
I saw the iceberg. And I see it in your eyes.

1348
01:50:58,710 --> 01:51:00,379
Please tell me the truth.

1349
01:51:08,554 --> 01:51:10,389
The ship will sink.

1350
01:51:12,141 --> 01:51:13,142
You're certain?

1351
01:51:14,226 --> 01:51:19,064
In an hour or so, all this
will be at the bottom of the Atlantic.

1352
01:51:21,733 --> 01:51:26,071
Please, tell only who you must.
I don't want to cause a panic.

1353
01:51:26,405 --> 01:51:29,241
And get to a boat. Quickly. Don't wait.

1354
01:51:29,908 --> 01:51:33,078
You remember what I told you about the boats?

1355
01:51:35,414 --> 01:51:36,748
Yes.

1356
01:51:38,584 --> 01:51:40,085
I understand.

1357
01:51:48,093 --> 01:51:49,428
Over here, son.

1358
01:51:50,429 --> 01:51:53,599
Sir, there's a big mob
at the Second Class Purser's office.

1359
01:51:53,932 --> 01:51:55,684
Go on. I'll watch him.

1360
01:51:56,435 --> 01:51:58,437
Aye. Right.

1361
01:52:12,117 --> 01:52:17,122
Sir, Carpathia says they're making 17 knots.
Full steam for them, sir.

1362
01:52:18,957 --> 01:52:20,375
She's the only one responding?

1363
01:52:20,626 --> 01:52:24,213
The only one close. They'll be here in four hours.

1364
01:52:24,963 --> 01:52:26,632
Four hours?!

1365
01:52:31,637 --> 01:52:33,138
Thank you, Bride.

1366
01:52:37,476 --> 01:52:39,144
My God.

1367
01:52:48,654 --> 01:52:50,656
We are swung out and ready, sir.

1368
01:52:52,157 --> 01:52:56,078
Hadn't we better get the women and children
into the boats?

1369
01:52:57,996 --> 01:52:58,997
Yes.

1370
01:53:03,168 --> 01:53:06,338
Women and children first, yes.

1371
01:53:07,840 --> 01:53:09,174
Yes, sir.

1372
01:53:12,010 --> 01:53:14,680
Ladies and gentlemen, attention, please!

1373
01:53:15,180 --> 01:53:17,683
Step this way, please. That's right.

1374
01:53:18,016 --> 01:53:20,853
Come towards me. Thank you.

1375
01:53:21,854 --> 01:53:22,855
Good.

1376
01:53:23,105 --> 01:53:27,359
For the time being,
I require only women and children.

1377
01:53:27,860 --> 01:53:29,027
Right here.

1378
01:53:29,695 --> 01:53:33,699
Like the Captain said,
nice and cheery, so there's no panic.

1379
01:53:34,700 --> 01:53:36,034
"Wedding Dance."

1380
01:53:44,418 --> 01:53:47,045
Lifebelts on. Put your lifebelts on.

1381
01:53:47,379 --> 01:53:50,048
Put your lifebelts on. Lifebelt on.

1382
01:53:50,382 --> 01:53:53,385
Here, put that lifebelt on. Turn it around.

1383
01:53:58,724 --> 01:54:01,059
It isn't time to go to the boats yet!

1384
01:54:01,393 --> 01:54:03,061
Please, stay calm.

1385
01:54:03,395 --> 01:54:06,565
Make sure you have your lifebelts on.

1386
01:54:06,899 --> 01:54:09,318
Let women and children through to the front.

1387
01:54:09,568 --> 01:54:10,903
What are we doing?

1388
01:54:11,153 --> 01:54:14,239
Waiting. Once first-class people
are in the boats...

1389
01:54:14,490 --> 01:54:17,826
...they'll start with us and we want to be ready.

1390
01:54:18,994 --> 01:54:21,246
Pushing won't get you out any faster.

1391
01:54:21,580 --> 01:54:22,915
Go get help.

1392
01:54:23,248 --> 01:54:27,252
Lower it away, left and right together! Steady.

1393
01:54:27,920 --> 01:54:30,923
Both sides together! Steady!

1394
01:54:31,256 --> 01:54:32,424
Steady!

1395
01:54:32,758 --> 01:54:34,092
Steady!

1396
01:54:35,594 --> 01:54:37,596
Stop, stop, stop!

1397
01:54:38,430 --> 01:54:39,598
Hold the left!

1398
01:54:39,932 --> 01:54:42,434
Right side only! Right side only!

1399
01:54:42,768 --> 01:54:43,936
Right side!

1400
01:54:44,269 --> 01:54:48,106
Hold the left! Right side down!
Lower away together!

1401
01:54:50,275 --> 01:54:51,944
Steady, lads!

1402
01:55:39,324 --> 01:55:42,828
You know, I do believe this ship may sink.

1403
01:55:44,830 --> 01:55:49,501
I've been asked to give you
this small token of our appreciation.

1404
01:55:52,004 --> 01:55:54,673
Compliments of Mr. Caledon Hockley.

1405
01:56:01,430 --> 01:56:04,099
Come on, sister, you heard
the man. Into the boat.

1406
01:56:04,433 --> 01:56:06,560
Any room for a gentleman,
gentlemen?

1407
01:56:06,768 --> 01:56:08,103
Only women at this time, sir.

1408
01:56:11,440 --> 01:56:13,817
Will the lifeboats be
seated according to class?

1409
01:56:15,736 --> 01:56:18,447
I hope they're not too crowded.

1410
01:56:19,239 --> 01:56:21,074
Oh, Mother, shut up!

1411
01:56:21,950 --> 01:56:23,118
Don't you understand?

1412
01:56:23,619 --> 01:56:25,329
The water is freezing and
there aren't enough boats.

1413
01:56:25,621 --> 01:56:27,247
Not enough by half.

1414
01:56:28,123 --> 01:56:30,626
Half the people on this
ship are going to die.

1415
01:56:30,959 --> 01:56:32,586
Not the better half.

1416
01:56:34,463 --> 01:56:35,506
Come on, Ruth,
get in the boat.

1417
01:56:36,089 --> 01:56:37,966
First class seats
are right up here.

1418
01:56:39,134 --> 01:56:40,969
You know, it's a pity I didn't
keep that drawing.

1419
01:56:41,094 --> 01:56:42,679
It'll be worth a lot
more by morning.

1420
01:56:46,642 --> 01:56:49,311
You unimaginable bastard.

1421
01:56:50,103 --> 01:56:52,105
Come on, Rose darling.
There's plenty of room for you.

1422
01:56:53,982 --> 01:56:55,025
Come on, Rose.

1423
01:56:55,526 --> 01:56:57,152
You're next, darling.

1424
01:56:57,486 --> 01:56:58,654
Come into the boat, Rose.

1425
01:57:01,114 --> 01:57:02,115
Come.

1426
01:57:02,449 --> 01:57:03,492
Rose.

1427
01:57:04,326 --> 01:57:05,619
Get into the boat!

1428
01:57:07,121 --> 01:57:08,122
Rose.

1429
01:57:09,289 --> 01:57:10,457
Good-bye, Mother.

1430
01:57:14,628 --> 01:57:16,130
Where are you going?

1431
01:57:16,839 --> 01:57:17,840
To him?!

1432
01:57:18,799 --> 01:57:20,300
To be a whore
to a gutter rat?

1433
01:57:21,510 --> 01:57:23,846
I'd rather be his whore
than your wife.

1434
01:57:26,223 --> 01:57:28,308
No!

1435
01:57:29,059 --> 01:57:31,061
I said, no!

1436
01:57:32,354 --> 01:57:34,690
Rose!
Please, stop!

1437
01:57:35,983 --> 01:57:37,317
And, lower away!

1438
01:57:38,652 --> 01:57:39,653
No, Wait!

1439
01:57:39,736 --> 01:57:40,737
Lower away!

1440
01:57:40,821 --> 01:57:42,698
- Rose!
- Lower together!

1441
01:57:43,365 --> 01:57:44,741
Hold the left side!

1442
01:57:48,662 --> 01:57:49,663
Help!

1443
01:57:50,539 --> 01:57:52,666
Can anybody hear me?!

1444
01:57:54,042 --> 01:57:55,711
Hello! Help me!

1445
01:57:56,545 --> 01:57:57,546
Help me!

1446
01:57:58,380 --> 01:58:00,382
Can you hear me?!

1447
01:58:00,716 --> 01:58:04,720
Can anybody hear me?!
Somebody help me!

1448
01:58:05,888 --> 01:58:07,389
Mr. Andrews?!

1449
01:58:11,059 --> 01:58:13,228
Steward, check the
starboard corridor.

1450
01:58:13,520 --> 01:58:16,023
Madame, please put on a lifebelt.
Get to the boat deck immediately.

1451
01:58:16,565 --> 01:58:19,193
Lucy, for God's sake put on your
lifebelt and set a good example.

1452
01:58:19,276 --> 01:58:20,277
Yes sir.

1453
01:58:20,903 --> 01:58:22,237
- Anyone in here?
- Mr. Andrews!

1454
01:58:22,571 --> 01:58:24,406
Mr. Andrews!
Thank God!

1455
01:58:24,698 --> 01:58:27,034
Where would the Master at Arms
take someone under arrest?

1456
01:58:27,618 --> 01:58:28,911
What? You have to get
to a boat right away.

1457
01:58:29,036 --> 01:58:30,037
No!

1458
01:58:30,078 --> 01:58:32,372
I'm doing this with or
without your help, sir.

1459
01:58:32,915 --> 01:58:33,916
But without will take longer.

1460
01:58:36,877 --> 01:58:39,046
Take the elevator to the
very bottom. Go to the left...

1461
01:58:39,213 --> 01:58:40,380
...down the crewmen's passage.

1462
01:58:40,422 --> 01:58:43,133
Then go right and left
again at the stairs.

1463
01:58:43,300 --> 01:58:44,551
You'll come
to a long corridor.

1464
01:58:49,431 --> 01:58:51,099
This could be bad.

1465
01:58:54,937 --> 01:58:57,606
Oh, shit!
Oh, shit!

1466
01:59:02,945 --> 01:59:04,947
Excuse me. Thank you.

1467
01:59:08,450 --> 01:59:11,453
I'm sorry, miss,
but the lifts are closed.

1468
01:59:12,287 --> 01:59:15,124
I'm through being polite,
goddamnit!

1469
01:59:15,249 --> 01:59:16,333
Now take me down!

1470
01:59:17,626 --> 01:59:18,961
E deck.

1471
01:59:22,297 --> 01:59:23,632
Come on.

1472
01:59:24,091 --> 01:59:25,425
Come on, come on.

1473
01:59:43,277 --> 01:59:44,611
I'm going back up.

1474
01:59:44,653 --> 01:59:46,822
No! No! No!

1475
01:59:50,993 --> 01:59:52,828
Come back!
I'm going back up!

1476
01:59:53,162 --> 01:59:54,163
I'm going back up!

1477
02:00:03,172 --> 02:00:04,173
Crew passage.

1478
02:00:27,529 --> 02:00:28,530
Jack!

1479
02:00:41,335 --> 02:00:42,336
Rose!

1480
02:00:44,755 --> 02:00:46,173
Rose, I'm in here!

1481
02:00:46,757 --> 02:00:48,091
I'm in here!

1482
02:00:48,634 --> 02:00:49,718
I'm in here!

1483
02:00:51,929 --> 02:00:53,931
Jack! I'm sorry.

1484
02:00:54,264 --> 02:00:56,600
I'm sorry. I'm so sorry.

1485
02:00:57,601 --> 02:00:58,977
That guy Lovejoy put
it in my pocket.

1486
02:00:59,019 --> 02:01:00,938
I know, I know, I know.

1487
02:01:01,021 --> 02:01:02,064
Listen Rose...

1488
02:01:02,189 --> 02:01:04,650
...you're gonna have to find
the spare key, all right?

1489
02:01:04,691 --> 02:01:06,026
Look in that
cabinet right there.

1490
02:01:07,569 --> 02:01:09,488
It's a little silver one, Rose.

1491
02:01:12,074 --> 02:01:13,575
These are all
brass ones!

1492
02:01:14,451 --> 02:01:15,953
Check right here, Rose.

1493
02:01:20,541 --> 02:01:21,542
Rose.

1494
02:01:22,876 --> 02:01:24,461
How did you find out I didn't do it?

1495
02:01:24,920 --> 02:01:25,921
I didn't.

1496
02:01:26,046 --> 02:01:28,048
I just realized
I already knew.

1497
02:01:30,634 --> 02:01:31,635
Keep looking.

1498
02:01:40,978 --> 02:01:42,020
No key.

1499
02:01:42,563 --> 02:01:43,564
There's no key!

1500
02:01:43,647 --> 02:01:44,648
All right, Rose, listen.

1501
02:01:44,982 --> 02:01:46,358
You're gonna have
to go find some help.

1502
02:01:47,234 --> 02:01:48,235
It'll be all right.

1503
02:01:53,657 --> 02:01:55,075
I'll be right back.

1504
02:02:02,666 --> 02:02:04,501
I'll just wait here!

1505
02:02:17,806 --> 02:02:19,016
Hello?
Is there anyone here?

1506
02:02:20,225 --> 02:02:21,226
Hello?

1507
02:02:21,852 --> 02:02:23,479
Is there anybody
down here?

1508
02:02:24,688 --> 02:02:26,482
We need help! Hello?

1509
02:02:28,192 --> 02:02:29,193
Damnit!

1510
02:02:35,699 --> 02:02:39,536
Can anybody hear me, please?!
Hello?! Hello?!

1511
02:02:41,538 --> 02:02:42,873
Oh, thank God.

1512
02:02:43,207 --> 02:02:44,333
Wait, please, I need your help.

1513
02:02:44,625 --> 02:02:45,626
There's a man back
here and he's...

1514
02:02:46,502 --> 02:02:47,503
Wait!

1515
02:02:51,715 --> 02:02:53,050
Hello?!

1516
02:03:18,826 --> 02:03:19,868
Hello?

1517
02:03:21,328 --> 02:03:22,830
Miss, you shouldn't
be here now.

1518
02:03:23,122 --> 02:03:24,331
I need your help.

1519
02:03:24,706 --> 02:03:26,458
There is a man down
here and he is trapped.

1520
02:03:26,667 --> 02:03:27,668
- This way, yes. All right.
- Please!

1521
02:03:28,001 --> 02:03:29,837
- There's no need to panic.
- No, I'm not panicking!

1522
02:03:30,087 --> 02:03:31,922
You're going the
wrong way!

1523
02:03:32,256 --> 02:03:34,007
Let go of me!
Listen!!!

1524
02:03:39,680 --> 02:03:40,681
To hell with you.

1525
02:04:18,635 --> 02:04:20,137
Oh, my God.

1526
02:05:12,189 --> 02:05:13,774
Will this work?

1527
02:05:14,691 --> 02:05:15,776
I guess we'll
find out.

1528
02:05:16,443 --> 02:05:17,444
Come on.

1529
02:05:20,531 --> 02:05:21,532
Wait, wait, wait.

1530
02:05:22,199 --> 02:05:23,700
Try a couple practice
swings over there.

1531
02:05:29,915 --> 02:05:30,916
Good.

1532
02:05:31,208 --> 02:05:33,001
Now try and hit the same mark
again, Rose. You can do it.

1533
02:05:39,716 --> 02:05:42,177
Okay, that's enough practice.
Come on, Rose.

1534
02:05:42,344 --> 02:05:43,929
You can do it.

1535
02:05:44,221 --> 02:05:47,891
Listen, just hit it really hard
and really fast.

1536
02:05:49,268 --> 02:05:50,561
Come on. Wait.

1537
02:05:50,644 --> 02:05:52,896
Open your
hands up a little more.

1538
02:05:53,230 --> 02:05:54,565
- Like that?
- Right.

1539
02:05:55,566 --> 02:05:57,609
Listen, Rose,
I trust you.

1540
02:06:02,573 --> 02:06:03,574
Go.

1541
02:06:09,913 --> 02:06:10,956
You did it!

1542
02:06:11,582 --> 02:06:12,916
Come on. Let's go.

1543
02:06:13,584 --> 02:06:15,586
Oh shit, this is cold!
Oh, shit!

1544
02:06:15,919 --> 02:06:17,504
Shit! Shit!

1545
02:06:23,093 --> 02:06:24,178
This is the way out.

1546
02:06:25,262 --> 02:06:27,764
We have to find
another way. Come on.

1547
02:06:30,809 --> 02:06:31,810
Pull.

1548
02:06:32,853 --> 02:06:33,854
Put your backs into it.

1549
02:06:39,818 --> 02:06:40,819
Pull!

1550
02:06:41,778 --> 02:06:44,615
Now, there's something
you don't see every day.

1551
02:07:06,470 --> 02:07:09,306
What's this luggage doing here?
Get rid of it. Get rid of it.

1552
02:07:09,431 --> 02:07:10,516
We need the room.
Get rid of that. Out.

1553
02:07:12,392 --> 02:07:15,395
This way.
Let go, sir. Get back.

1554
02:07:15,646 --> 02:07:16,980
Keep calm!

1555
02:07:24,321 --> 02:07:25,322
Lovejoy!

1556
02:07:25,697 --> 02:07:27,699
She's not on the starboard side either.

1557
02:07:27,991 --> 02:07:31,995
We're running out of time. This strutting
martinet isn't letting any men on at all.

1558
02:07:32,663 --> 02:07:34,665
There's one on the other
side letting men on.

1559
02:07:35,332 --> 02:07:36,625
Well then, that's our play.

1560
02:07:36,792 --> 02:07:39,461
We'll need some
insurance first. Come on.

1561
02:07:40,337 --> 02:07:42,422
This way, please.
All the way down here.

1562
02:07:45,509 --> 02:07:46,510
Here!

1563
02:07:47,719 --> 02:07:49,012
What do you
think you're doing?

1564
02:07:49,513 --> 02:07:51,515
You'll have to pay for
that, you know.

1565
02:07:51,765 --> 02:07:53,517
That's White Star
Line property.

1566
02:07:53,851 --> 02:07:55,352
Shut up!

1567
02:07:56,186 --> 02:07:59,356
Will you hold the boat a moment?
I just have to run back to my room...

1568
02:08:00,190 --> 02:08:01,233
Sit down!

1569
02:08:01,859 --> 02:08:02,901
She's the last.

1570
02:08:03,068 --> 02:08:04,820
- Prepare to lower.
- Mr. Lightoller.

1571
02:08:04,987 --> 02:08:06,905
Why are the boats being
launched half full?

1572
02:08:07,197 --> 02:08:08,198
Not now, Mr. Andrews.

1573
02:08:08,449 --> 02:08:11,618
There, look. 20 or so
in a boat built for 65?

1574
02:08:11,869 --> 02:08:13,871
And I saw one boat
with only 12. 12!

1575
02:08:14,204 --> 02:08:17,249
Well, we weren't sure of
the weight, Mr. Andrews.

1576
02:08:17,458 --> 02:08:18,584
These boats may
buckle.

1577
02:08:18,792 --> 02:08:19,793
Rubbish!

1578
02:08:20,043 --> 02:08:22,713
They were tested in Belfast
with the weight of 70 men.

1579
02:08:23,130 --> 02:08:25,591
Now, fill these boats, Mr. Lightoller.
For God's sake man!

1580
02:08:32,890 --> 02:08:35,726
Please, I need more women
and children, please!

1581
02:08:41,064 --> 02:08:42,232
Get back in there!

1582
02:08:42,566 --> 02:08:45,068
This is not an exit.
This is not an exit.

1583
02:08:47,654 --> 02:08:50,324
You can't keep us locked in here.
Like animals. The ship's bloody sinking.

1584
02:08:51,575 --> 02:08:53,577
Bring forward the women!

1585
02:08:53,911 --> 02:08:55,412
Unlock the gates.

1586
02:08:56,246 --> 02:08:58,248
Women only!

1587
02:08:58,916 --> 02:09:00,584
No men!

1588
02:09:00,918 --> 02:09:02,419
No men!

1589
02:09:06,924 --> 02:09:08,801
Get back!

1590
02:09:10,093 --> 02:09:11,178
Get back!

1591
02:09:11,261 --> 02:09:12,638
Lock the gates!

1592
02:09:13,430 --> 02:09:14,807
Get them back
from those gates!

1593
02:09:16,183 --> 02:09:17,476
Don't touch the gates!

1594
02:09:21,104 --> 02:09:22,481
For God's sake, man...

1595
02:09:22,606 --> 02:09:24,149
...there are women and
children down here!

1596
02:09:24,441 --> 02:09:26,777
Let us up so we can have a chance!

1597
02:09:27,820 --> 02:09:28,821
Get back!

1598
02:09:32,574 --> 02:09:33,700
Tommy!

1599
02:09:33,784 --> 02:09:35,285
- Can we get out?
- It's hopeless that way.

1600
02:09:35,619 --> 02:09:37,037
Whatever we do,
we've got to do it fast.

1601
02:09:40,791 --> 02:09:42,209
The boats are all going.

1602
02:09:42,543 --> 02:09:44,294
This whole place is flooding.
We've gotta get out of here.

1603
02:09:44,461 --> 02:09:45,504
There is niente this way.

1604
02:09:46,630 --> 02:09:47,881
Let's go this way, all right?
Come on!

1605
02:09:53,971 --> 02:09:55,139
I make my own luck.

1606
02:09:55,472 --> 02:09:56,974
So do I.

1607
02:10:04,815 --> 02:10:06,150
Come on!

1608
02:10:06,650 --> 02:10:07,693
No, come on, let's go this way.

1609
02:10:17,244 --> 02:10:18,412
This way!

1610
02:10:19,288 --> 02:10:20,664
Just go back to
the main stairwell.

1611
02:10:21,832 --> 02:10:23,125
And everything will be
sorted out there.

1612
02:10:24,585 --> 02:10:26,420
It will all get sorted out back there.

1613
02:10:26,795 --> 02:10:27,921
Go back to the main stairwell.

1614
02:10:28,046 --> 02:10:30,007
- Open the gate!
- Go back down the main stairwell.

1615
02:10:30,257 --> 02:10:31,592
Open the gate right now!

1616
02:10:31,842 --> 02:10:33,927
Go back down the main
stairwell, like I told you.

1617
02:10:36,180 --> 02:10:38,682
Goddamn it! Son of a bitch!

1618
02:10:39,016 --> 02:10:40,684
Stop that!

1619
02:10:44,605 --> 02:10:45,647
Fabri, Tommy,
give me a hand here.

1620
02:10:45,731 --> 02:10:46,732
Move aside.

1621
02:10:46,815 --> 02:10:48,984
Come on, pull!

1622
02:10:49,860 --> 02:10:50,861
Pull!

1623
02:10:51,862 --> 02:10:53,155
Move aside.
Quickly, move aside!

1624
02:10:53,280 --> 02:10:54,281
Put that down!

1625
02:10:54,364 --> 02:10:55,616
- Move aside!
- Put that down!

1626
02:10:55,699 --> 02:10:57,034
One! Two!

1627
02:10:57,951 --> 02:10:59,119
Three!

1628
02:11:01,371 --> 02:11:02,539
Again!

1629
02:11:04,541 --> 02:11:05,584
Now, let's go!

1630
02:11:07,920 --> 02:11:08,962
Let's go, Rose.

1631
02:11:09,046 --> 02:11:11,215
You can't go up there!
You can't do this!

1632
02:11:17,554 --> 02:11:19,389
Keep order! Keep order here!

1633
02:11:19,723 --> 02:11:22,559
Back! Back! Back!

1634
02:11:27,147 --> 02:11:28,148
Hold on to her!

1635
02:11:29,733 --> 02:11:30,776
Pull her in!

1636
02:11:31,735 --> 02:11:34,238
Get back, I say, or I'll...

1637
02:11:34,571 --> 02:11:36,740
...shoot you all like dogs!

1638
02:11:37,074 --> 02:11:38,575
Keep order here!

1639
02:11:39,576 --> 02:11:41,745
Keep order, I say.

1640
02:11:42,579 --> 02:11:44,748
Mr. Lowe, man this boat.

1641
02:11:49,253 --> 02:11:53,423
Right. Is everybody all right?
Nobody panic.

1642
02:11:59,596 --> 02:12:01,265
Stay back.

1643
02:12:01,765 --> 02:12:02,933
We're too late.

1644
02:12:03,183 --> 02:12:06,270
There are more boats down the front.
Stay with this one. Murdoch.

1645
02:12:06,520 --> 02:12:08,063
He seems to be quite practical.

1646
02:12:12,776 --> 02:12:14,278
Don't lower it!

1647
02:12:14,778 --> 02:12:16,780
Cut the falls!

1648
02:12:22,286 --> 02:12:24,121
Sit down!

1649
02:12:25,456 --> 02:12:26,874
Stay back, you lot!

1650
02:12:27,124 --> 02:12:30,294
Just stay back, the
lot of you! Stay back!

1651
02:12:32,963 --> 02:12:35,632
It's starting to fall apart.
We don't have much time.

1652
02:12:37,301 --> 02:12:38,635
Mr. Murdoch?

1653
02:12:38,969 --> 02:12:41,472
Mr. Hockley.
You two, with me, now!

1654
02:12:41,722 --> 02:12:43,307
I'm a businessman, as you know...

1655
02:12:43,474 --> 02:12:45,058
...and I have a business
proposition for you.

1656
02:12:52,816 --> 02:12:53,984
Come on, Rose.

1657
02:12:57,488 --> 02:12:58,489
The boats are gone!

1658
02:13:04,161 --> 02:13:05,829
Colonel, are there
any boats on that side?

1659
02:13:06,079 --> 02:13:08,457
No, miss, but there are a couple
of boats all the way forward.

1660
02:13:08,624 --> 02:13:10,209
This way, I'll lead you.

1661
02:13:16,423 --> 02:13:19,760
What's the use?
Nobody's listening to us anyway.

1662
02:13:20,010 --> 02:13:21,553
Well, they don't listen to
us at dinner, either.

1663
02:13:21,678 --> 02:13:22,763
Come on, let's play.

1664
02:13:22,888 --> 02:13:24,223
Keep us warm.

1665
02:13:25,015 --> 02:13:26,350
"Orpheus."

1666
02:13:31,188 --> 02:13:33,982
Music to drown by.
Now I know I'm in first class.

1667
02:13:39,863 --> 02:13:43,200
- Where is everyone?
- They're all still aft, sir.

1668
02:13:45,202 --> 02:13:47,371
We have an understanding
then, Mr. Murdoch.

1669
02:13:58,715 --> 02:14:02,719
Will the men please hold
back! Hold back, I say!

1670
02:14:05,055 --> 02:14:07,850
Women and children only!

1671
02:14:08,016 --> 02:14:09,935
Get back!

1672
02:14:10,227 --> 02:14:12,896
Come through, madame.
This way. Step back, sir!

1673
02:14:14,398 --> 02:14:17,234
You better check the
other side. Go!

1674
02:14:24,575 --> 02:14:26,410
I found her, on the other side.

1675
02:14:27,077 --> 02:14:28,495
Waiting for a boat.

1676
02:14:28,996 --> 02:14:29,997
With him.

1677
02:14:31,665 --> 02:14:33,750
- Any more women and children?
- They're all aboard, Mr. Murdoch.

1678
02:14:34,084 --> 02:14:35,919
Anyone else then?

1679
02:14:37,504 --> 02:14:38,922
- Anyone else?
- Do hurry. Hurry along.

1680
02:14:45,095 --> 02:14:47,097
Goddamn it all to hell.

1681
02:14:49,766 --> 02:14:51,101
Shit.

1682
02:14:51,393 --> 02:14:52,394
Fire!

1683
02:14:53,812 --> 02:14:55,731
Sir, sir, you can't
go through here.

1684
02:14:59,359 --> 02:15:01,695
That's it.
Splendid. Right.

1685
02:15:05,616 --> 02:15:07,284
Prepare to lower.

1686
02:15:09,453 --> 02:15:11,288
Ready on the left.

1687
02:15:17,211 --> 02:15:18,879
Take them down.

1688
02:15:23,717 --> 02:15:25,052
Keep it steady.

1689
02:15:27,721 --> 02:15:31,642
Both sides together.
Steady. Keep it steady.

1690
02:15:32,684 --> 02:15:34,019
- Give her to me.
- Daddy.

1691
02:15:34,853 --> 02:15:37,189
It'll be fine, darling.
Don't you worry.

1692
02:15:37,523 --> 02:15:39,191
Daddy, get in the boat.

1693
02:15:39,525 --> 02:15:42,361
It's good-bye for a little
while. Only for a little while.

1694
02:15:42,611 --> 02:15:44,655
There'll be another
boat for the daddies.

1695
02:15:45,239 --> 02:15:46,406
This boat is for the
mummies and the children.

1696
02:15:46,532 --> 02:15:48,617
You hold Mummy's hand
and be a good little girl.

1697
02:15:50,119 --> 02:15:51,453
I'm not going without you.

1698
02:15:51,703 --> 02:15:53,247
No, you have
to go, now.

1699
02:15:53,372 --> 02:15:54,373
No, Jack.

1700
02:15:54,498 --> 02:15:55,791
Get in the
boat, Rose.

1701
02:15:55,874 --> 02:15:57,042
No, Jack.

1702
02:15:57,126 --> 02:15:58,127
Yes.

1703
02:15:58,210 --> 02:15:59,211
Get on the boat!

1704
02:15:59,294 --> 02:16:01,630
Yes, get on
the boat, Rose.

1705
02:16:04,466 --> 02:16:05,634
Oh my God, look at you.

1706
02:16:05,884 --> 02:16:07,719
You look a fright.

1707
02:16:07,803 --> 02:16:08,804
Here.

1708
02:16:10,556 --> 02:16:12,724
Put this on. Come.

1709
02:16:17,729 --> 02:16:19,565
Go on. I'll get the next one.

1710
02:16:19,815 --> 02:16:21,650
No, not without you.

1711
02:16:21,900 --> 02:16:23,735
I'll be all right.
Listen, I'll be fine.

1712
02:16:24,069 --> 02:16:25,904
I'm a survivor, all right?
Don't worry about me.

1713
02:16:26,238 --> 02:16:27,531
Now, go on.
Get on.

1714
02:16:28,073 --> 02:16:29,700
I have an arrangement with an
officer on the other side of the ship.

1715
02:16:30,159 --> 02:16:31,702
Jack and I can
get off safely.

1716
02:16:32,244 --> 02:16:33,245
Both of us.

1717
02:16:34,413 --> 02:16:35,497
See?

1718
02:16:35,581 --> 02:16:36,623
I got my own
boat to catch.

1719
02:16:37,416 --> 02:16:38,417
Go on, hurry.

1720
02:16:38,500 --> 02:16:39,918
They're almost full.

1721
02:16:41,420 --> 02:16:42,546
- Step aboard, miss.
- Go. Go.

1722
02:16:44,423 --> 02:16:45,591
Step aboard, please.

1723
02:16:45,883 --> 02:16:47,301
You're daddy's
good girl, all right?

1724
02:16:47,384 --> 02:16:48,510
You're my little sailor.

1725
02:16:52,764 --> 02:16:53,765
Clear the rail, please.

1726
02:16:55,434 --> 02:16:56,685
And, lower away!

1727
02:17:10,532 --> 02:17:11,867
You're a good liar.

1728
02:17:12,618 --> 02:17:14,453
Almost as good as you.

1729
02:17:19,124 --> 02:17:22,795
There's no... there's no
arrangement, is there?

1730
02:17:24,129 --> 02:17:25,631
No, there is.

1731
02:17:25,964 --> 02:17:28,133
Not that you'll benefit much from it.

1732
02:17:30,052 --> 02:17:31,720
I always win, Jack.

1733
02:17:32,805 --> 02:17:34,473
One way or another.

1734
02:18:32,614 --> 02:18:33,657
Rose!

1735
02:18:36,034 --> 02:18:37,035
Stop her!

1736
02:18:37,786 --> 02:18:38,787
Rose, what
are you doing?!

1737
02:18:40,873 --> 02:18:41,874
No!

1738
02:19:04,897 --> 02:19:07,566
Rose! You're so stupid!
Why did you do that, huh?

1739
02:19:07,900 --> 02:19:09,902
You're so stupid, Rose.

1740
02:19:11,236 --> 02:19:12,905
Why did you
do that? Why?!

1741
02:19:14,239 --> 02:19:16,241
You jump,
I jump, right?

1742
02:19:18,076 --> 02:19:19,119
Right.

1743
02:19:21,789 --> 02:19:23,373
Oh God.
I couldn't go.

1744
02:19:24,333 --> 02:19:25,834
I couldn't
go, Jack.

1745
02:19:25,918 --> 02:19:27,586
It's all right. We'll
think of something.

1746
02:19:29,254 --> 02:19:30,756
- At least I'm with you.
- We'll think of something.

1747
02:19:45,229 --> 02:19:46,271
Come on! Move!

1748
02:19:49,608 --> 02:19:50,609
Come on!
Move.

1749
02:19:57,407 --> 02:19:58,408
Come on!

1750
02:20:06,542 --> 02:20:07,543
Move!

1751
02:20:13,799 --> 02:20:15,300
Come on!
Come on Rose.

1752
02:20:17,886 --> 02:20:18,887
Rose, come on!

1753
02:20:21,890 --> 02:20:22,933
Move Rose!

1754
02:20:26,019 --> 02:20:27,020
Go!

1755
02:20:37,614 --> 02:20:40,325
I hope you enjoy your time together!

1756
02:20:54,339 --> 02:20:56,675
What could
possibly be funny?

1757
02:20:58,093 --> 02:20:59,845
I put the diamond
in the coat.

1758
02:21:02,598 --> 02:21:04,516
And I put the
coat on her!

1759
02:21:06,268 --> 02:21:07,352
Come on!

1760
02:21:27,623 --> 02:21:29,041
Dada!

1761
02:21:31,376 --> 02:21:32,503
We can't leave him.

1762
02:21:37,049 --> 02:21:38,383
All right, come on!

1763
02:21:40,052 --> 02:21:42,221
Dada!

1764
02:21:55,317 --> 02:21:56,652
Go back!

1765
02:22:07,371 --> 02:22:08,539
It's the wrong way!
Come back!

1766
02:22:08,622 --> 02:22:11,208
No, not that way!
Come back! Stop!

1767
02:22:16,255 --> 02:22:17,422
Go!

1768
02:22:19,758 --> 02:22:23,428
Go! Run!

1769
02:22:49,121 --> 02:22:50,122
This way!

1770
02:23:02,301 --> 02:23:03,469
Give me your hand!

1771
02:23:12,478 --> 02:23:13,812
Oh, God!

1772
02:23:18,150 --> 02:23:19,318
Help!

1773
02:23:25,157 --> 02:23:26,492
Help!

1774
02:23:27,951 --> 02:23:29,036
Wait, sir!

1775
02:23:29,119 --> 02:23:30,662
Sir, open the gate, please!

1776
02:23:30,913 --> 02:23:32,080
Help us, please!

1777
02:23:32,331 --> 02:23:33,499
Help us!

1778
02:23:33,665 --> 02:23:34,833
- Please!
- Please!

1779
02:23:36,502 --> 02:23:37,836
Bloody hell!

1780
02:23:43,509 --> 02:23:45,511
- Come on, come on!
- Come on!

1781
02:23:45,844 --> 02:23:47,179
Go, go!

1782
02:23:47,429 --> 02:23:48,430
Jesus.

1783
02:23:49,515 --> 02:23:50,516
- Please!
- Come on!

1784
02:23:50,766 --> 02:23:52,017
Hurry!

1785
02:23:52,893 --> 02:23:53,936
Come on!

1786
02:23:58,524 --> 02:24:00,275
I'm sorry, I
dropped the keys.

1787
02:24:01,527 --> 02:24:03,695
- Wait, please!
- Wait!

1788
02:24:04,029 --> 02:24:06,532
Don't leave! Please,
send for help!

1789
02:24:25,217 --> 02:24:27,219
I got it! Which
one is it, Rose?

1790
02:24:27,553 --> 02:24:29,555
The short one.
Try the short one.

1791
02:24:30,556 --> 02:24:31,557
Hurry, Jack.

1792
02:24:35,227 --> 02:24:36,895
Oh no! It won't go in.

1793
02:24:37,813 --> 02:24:38,814
Hurry, Jack.

1794
02:24:41,400 --> 02:24:43,318
It's stuck! It's stuck!

1795
02:24:44,570 --> 02:24:46,238
- Come on!
- Hurry, Jack!

1796
02:24:47,906 --> 02:24:49,575
- Hurry, Jack!
- Come on!

1797
02:24:52,244 --> 02:24:54,246
I got it! I got it!
Go! Go, Rose!

1798
02:24:55,247 --> 02:24:56,582
Go! Go!

1799
02:25:08,927 --> 02:25:11,263
Jack! Come on!

1800
02:25:13,265 --> 02:25:14,766
Move, move.

1801
02:25:24,610 --> 02:25:26,445
- Get those oars in place.
- Get an oar under it.

1802
02:25:31,617 --> 02:25:33,285
Hold it! Hold it!

1803
02:25:33,619 --> 02:25:34,953
Hold it!

1804
02:25:44,880 --> 02:25:49,134
Get these davits cranked in!
Let's get the falls hooked up!

1805
02:26:01,313 --> 02:26:03,148
Mommy!

1806
02:26:09,822 --> 02:26:10,906
Keep going up!

1807
02:26:14,159 --> 02:26:15,661
Stop pushing!

1808
02:26:17,830 --> 02:26:19,164
Stay back!

1809
02:26:19,414 --> 02:26:21,917
Will you give us a chance
to live, you limey bastard!

1810
02:26:22,167 --> 02:26:24,670
I'll shoot any man who tries
to get past me! Get back!

1811
02:26:24,837 --> 02:26:25,921
Bastard!

1812
02:26:26,171 --> 02:26:27,673
Get back!

1813
02:26:27,840 --> 02:26:28,924
We had a deal,
damn you!

1814
02:26:32,344 --> 02:26:35,347
Your money can't save you
any more than it could save me.

1815
02:26:35,472 --> 02:26:36,473
Get back!

1816
02:26:37,683 --> 02:26:39,601
Women and children only!

1817
02:26:48,527 --> 02:26:49,862
No, Tommy!

1818
02:27:08,589 --> 02:27:09,590
No, Will!

1819
02:27:16,472 --> 02:27:17,973
Now stand
back, damn you!

1820
02:27:21,310 --> 02:27:24,813
Gently, gently. Hold it. Hold it.

1821
02:27:34,490 --> 02:27:36,158
I have a child!

1822
02:27:36,492 --> 02:27:38,619
- I have a child!
- Clear a path here!

1823
02:27:38,994 --> 02:27:40,996
Please, I have a child!

1824
02:27:41,830 --> 02:27:44,500
Please. I'm all she has in the world.

1825
02:27:45,459 --> 02:27:46,502
Go on.

1826
02:27:46,835 --> 02:27:47,836
Step back!

1827
02:27:48,337 --> 02:27:49,671
- Please?
- Here, give her to me.

1828
02:27:50,380 --> 02:27:51,799
You're all right, dearie.

1829
02:27:54,885 --> 02:27:55,969
Give her here.

1830
02:27:57,888 --> 02:27:58,889
There, there.

1831
02:28:03,185 --> 02:28:06,021
Wait, wait, wait! Mr. Andrews!

1832
02:28:08,524 --> 02:28:09,525
Oh, Rose.

1833
02:28:12,528 --> 02:28:13,862
Won't you even
make a try for it?

1834
02:28:15,864 --> 02:28:20,369
I'm sorry that I didn't build you
a stronger ship, young Rose.

1835
02:28:22,204 --> 02:28:24,540
It's going fast.
We have to move.

1836
02:28:24,832 --> 02:28:25,833
Wait.

1837
02:28:28,877 --> 02:28:30,337
Good luck to you, Rose.

1838
02:28:32,381 --> 02:28:33,382
And to you.

1839
02:28:46,353 --> 02:28:47,396
Mr. Guggenheim?

1840
02:28:47,855 --> 02:28:49,022
These are for you, Mr. Guggenheim.

1841
02:28:49,231 --> 02:28:50,232
No, thank you.

1842
02:28:50,399 --> 02:28:54,278
We are dressed in our best and are
prepared to go down as gentlemen.

1843
02:28:55,070 --> 02:28:57,030
But we would
like a brandy.

1844
02:28:57,739 --> 02:29:00,242
Get the falls over here now!

1845
02:29:00,909 --> 02:29:03,370
Let them drop. Then we'll right it.

1846
02:29:08,625 --> 02:29:09,751
Capitán?

1847
02:29:10,252 --> 02:29:12,588
Capitán, where should I go? Please.

1848
02:29:19,928 --> 02:29:21,930
Captain. Captain. Sir.

1849
02:29:52,419 --> 02:29:54,630
Right.
That's it, then.

1850
02:29:55,464 --> 02:29:57,090
Good-bye, Wally.
Good luck.

1851
02:29:58,133 --> 02:29:59,301
- Good-bye, Wallace.
- So long, old chap.

1852
02:31:14,543 --> 02:31:19,047
And so they lived happily
together for 300 years...

1853
02:31:19,381 --> 02:31:21,550
...in the land of Tir na nog...

1854
02:31:22,551 --> 02:31:25,220
Land of eternal
youth and beauty.

1855
02:32:00,589 --> 02:32:01,924
There's no time!

1856
02:32:02,090 --> 02:32:03,467
Cut those falls!

1857
02:32:03,717 --> 02:32:05,886
Cut them!
Cut them if you have to!

1858
02:32:06,595 --> 02:32:09,264
I need a knife!

1859
02:32:10,933 --> 02:32:12,601
Cut the falls now!

1860
02:32:13,227 --> 02:32:14,603
Cut them loose!

1861
02:32:25,114 --> 02:32:26,949
Cut those bloody falls!

1862
02:33:14,621 --> 02:33:15,956
Gentlemen...

1863
02:33:16,457 --> 02:33:19,126
...it has been a privilege
playing with you tonight.

1864
02:34:19,937 --> 02:34:21,814
We have to stay on the
ship as long as possible.

1865
02:34:21,980 --> 02:34:22,981
Come on!

1866
02:34:35,035 --> 02:34:36,703
This way.
Through the rail.

1867
02:34:38,956 --> 02:34:40,290
Come on, Rose.

1868
02:34:40,624 --> 02:34:41,625
Jump.

1869
02:34:43,961 --> 02:34:45,045
Come on.

1870
02:35:18,328 --> 02:35:19,913
I got you.
Jump.

1871
02:35:22,583 --> 02:35:24,418
I've got you, miss.

1872
02:35:28,255 --> 02:35:29,423
Back!

1873
02:35:59,620 --> 02:36:01,288
No! You'll swamp us!

1874
02:36:14,051 --> 02:36:17,137
Yea, though I walk through the
valley of the shadow of death...

1875
02:36:17,471 --> 02:36:20,224
You wanna walk a little faster
through that valley there?

1876
02:37:10,524 --> 02:37:12,025
Holy Mary, mother of God...

1877
02:37:12,192 --> 02:37:15,154
...pray for us sinners now and
at the hour of our death. Amen.

1878
02:37:15,863 --> 02:37:16,947
Hail Mary, full of grace...

1879
02:37:17,030 --> 02:37:18,115
This way.

1880
02:37:28,459 --> 02:37:29,460
Come on!

1881
02:37:29,543 --> 02:37:30,544
Come on!

1882
02:37:40,220 --> 02:37:42,639
And I saw a new heaven
and a new earth...

1883
02:37:42,890 --> 02:37:46,393
...for the first heaven and the first earth
had passed away...

1884
02:37:47,478 --> 02:37:49,062
...and there was no more sea.

1885
02:37:55,569 --> 02:37:58,655
It'll be over soon.
It'll all be over soon.

1886
02:38:04,244 --> 02:38:05,746
And He shall dwell with them.

1887
02:38:05,913 --> 02:38:10,334
And they shall be His people
and God Himself shall be with them...

1888
02:38:10,667 --> 02:38:12,085
...and be their God.

1889
02:38:12,836 --> 02:38:13,921
Jack...

1890
02:38:14,922 --> 02:38:16,924
...this is where
we first met.

1891
02:38:23,972 --> 02:38:27,184
And God shall wipe away
all the tears from their eyes...

1892
02:38:27,518 --> 02:38:29,603
...and there shall be
no more death.

1893
02:38:30,104 --> 02:38:32,606
Neither shall there be
sorrow or crying.

1894
02:38:33,107 --> 02:38:35,609
Neither shall there
be any more pain...

1895
02:38:36,443 --> 02:38:39,196
...for the former world
has passed away.

1896
02:38:53,627 --> 02:38:55,963
Bloody pull faster!
And pull!

1897
02:39:19,236 --> 02:39:20,571
Hang on, miss Trudy!

1898
02:39:56,523 --> 02:39:58,025
Hold on real tight.

1899
02:40:15,542 --> 02:40:17,377
God Almighty.

1900
02:40:24,843 --> 02:40:27,387
Keep those breakers in!
Keep them in!

1901
02:41:46,383 --> 02:41:47,801
We have to move!

1902
02:41:53,724 --> 02:41:55,100
Give me your hand.
I'll pull you over.

1903
02:41:55,142 --> 02:41:56,143
I can't.

1904
02:41:56,268 --> 02:41:57,269
Come on!

1905
02:41:57,352 --> 02:41:58,395
Give me your hand.

1906
02:42:00,147 --> 02:42:02,149
I've got you.
I won't let go.

1907
02:42:02,733 --> 02:42:03,776
Come on,
I've got you.

1908
02:42:14,995 --> 02:42:18,165
- What's happening, Jack?
- I don't know. I don't know.

1909
02:42:27,341 --> 02:42:28,342
Hold on.

1910
02:43:10,717 --> 02:43:11,885
This is it!

1911
02:43:23,897 --> 02:43:27,568
Oh, my God, Jack!
Oh, God. Oh, God.

1912
02:43:28,235 --> 02:43:29,570
Hold on!

1913
02:43:44,585 --> 02:43:46,545
The ship is gonna suck us down.

1914
02:43:46,587 --> 02:43:48,797
Take a deep
breath when I say.

1915
02:43:54,428 --> 02:43:56,597
Kick for the surface
and keep kicking.

1916
02:43:56,638 --> 02:43:57,973
Do not let go
of my hand.

1917
02:44:05,689 --> 02:44:06,940
We're going to make it, Rose.

1918
02:44:06,982 --> 02:44:07,983
Trust me.

1919
02:44:08,108 --> 02:44:09,359
I trust you.

1920
02:44:14,448 --> 02:44:16,450
Ready! Ready!

1921
02:44:16,950 --> 02:44:17,951
Now!

1922
02:44:54,321 --> 02:44:56,156
Jack! Jack!

1923
02:45:39,199 --> 02:45:40,200
Rose!

1924
02:45:40,701 --> 02:45:43,036
Get off her!
Get off her!

1925
02:45:47,249 --> 02:45:48,917
Swim, Rose! I need
you to swim!

1926
02:45:53,714 --> 02:45:55,382
Keep swimming.

1927
02:45:59,052 --> 02:46:00,387
It's so cold.

1928
02:46:00,637 --> 02:46:01,972
Swim, Rose!

1929
02:46:06,560 --> 02:46:07,895
Come on.

1930
02:46:09,897 --> 02:46:10,981
Keep swimming.

1931
02:46:11,231 --> 02:46:12,566
Come on.

1932
02:46:14,526 --> 02:46:15,569
Here...

1933
02:46:15,694 --> 02:46:16,862
...get on it.

1934
02:46:17,571 --> 02:46:19,072
Get on top.

1935
02:46:26,455 --> 02:46:27,915
Come on, Rose.

1936
02:46:37,466 --> 02:46:39,134
Stay on it.
Stay on, Rose.

1937
02:47:00,989 --> 02:47:02,491
It'll be all right now.

1938
02:47:04,993 --> 02:47:06,495
It'll be all right now.

1939
02:47:13,836 --> 02:47:15,003
Return...

1940
02:47:15,212 --> 02:47:16,880
...the boats!

1941
02:47:21,009 --> 02:47:23,137
The boats are coming
back for us Rose.

1942
02:47:23,679 --> 02:47:25,139
Hold on just a
little bit longer.

1943
02:47:26,014 --> 02:47:28,684
They had to row
away for the suction...

1944
02:47:28,892 --> 02:47:30,978
...but now they'll
be coming back.

1945
02:47:34,022 --> 02:47:35,357
For God's sake!

1946
02:47:35,649 --> 02:47:36,859
Please...

1947
02:47:37,192 --> 02:47:38,485
...help us!

1948
02:47:43,866 --> 02:47:45,576
You don't understand.

1949
02:47:46,410 --> 02:47:48,579
If we go back, they'll
swamp the boat.

1950
02:47:48,829 --> 02:47:50,164
They'll pull us right down,
I'm telling you.

1951
02:47:50,706 --> 02:47:53,208
Oh, knock it off.
You're scaring me.

1952
02:47:53,542 --> 02:47:56,044
Come on, girls, grab
an oar. Let's go.

1953
02:47:56,336 --> 02:47:59,506
Are you out of your mind?
We're in the middle of the North Atlantic.

1954
02:47:59,715 --> 02:48:03,051
Now, do you people want to live
or do you want to die?!

1955
02:48:10,017 --> 02:48:12,227
I don't understand a one of you.

1956
02:48:14,062 --> 02:48:15,189
What's the matter with you?

1957
02:48:16,190 --> 02:48:17,608
It's your men out there!

1958
02:48:20,068 --> 02:48:21,737
There's plenty of room for more.

1959
02:48:22,029 --> 02:48:23,697
And there'll be one less
on this boat...

1960
02:48:24,031 --> 02:48:27,409
...if you don't shut that
hole in your face!

1961
02:48:43,258 --> 02:48:47,387
Now, bring in your oars over there.
And tie these boats together as well.

1962
02:48:51,767 --> 02:48:54,103
Now, make sure that's
tied up nice and tight.

1963
02:48:57,606 --> 02:49:00,275
Right, listen to me, men.
We have to go back.

1964
02:49:00,609 --> 02:49:04,113
I want to transfer all the women
from this boat into that boat right now...

1965
02:49:04,238 --> 02:49:05,405
...as quick as you can, please.

1966
02:49:05,447 --> 02:49:07,950
Let's create some space over there.
Move forward and aft.

1967
02:49:17,960 --> 02:49:19,795
It's getting quiet.

1968
02:49:21,964 --> 02:49:25,300
It's just going to take a
couple of minutes...

1969
02:49:25,801 --> 02:49:27,803
...to get the boats organized.

1970
02:49:30,639 --> 02:49:32,307
I don't know about you but...

1971
02:49:32,641 --> 02:49:36,145
...I intend to write
a strongly worded letter...

1972
02:49:36,478 --> 02:49:38,105
...to the White Star Line
about all this.

1973
02:49:46,488 --> 02:49:48,157
I love you, Jack.

1974
02:49:54,830 --> 02:49:56,331
Don't you do that.

1975
02:49:57,833 --> 02:50:01,003
Don't you say your
good-byes. Not yet.

1976
02:50:01,336 --> 02:50:02,838
Do you understand me?

1977
02:50:03,172 --> 02:50:05,007
I'm so cold.

1978
02:50:05,507 --> 02:50:07,009
Listen, Rose...

1979
02:50:08,177 --> 02:50:09,845
...you're gonna
get out of here.

1980
02:50:11,013 --> 02:50:12,514
You're gonna go on...

1981
02:50:13,849 --> 02:50:15,642
...and you're gonna
make lots of babies.

1982
02:50:16,351 --> 02:50:18,353
And you're gonna
watch them grow.

1983
02:50:20,022 --> 02:50:21,148
You're gonna die an old...

1984
02:50:21,315 --> 02:50:22,566
...an old lady.

1985
02:50:22,858 --> 02:50:24,526
...warm in her bed.

1986
02:50:26,195 --> 02:50:27,321
Not here.

1987
02:50:28,197 --> 02:50:30,699
Not this night.
Not like this.

1988
02:50:31,033 --> 02:50:32,701
Do you understand me?

1989
02:50:35,704 --> 02:50:37,873
I can't feel my body.

1990
02:50:39,541 --> 02:50:41,001
Winning that ticket, Rose...

1991
02:50:41,168 --> 02:50:43,754
...was the best thing that
ever happened to me.

1992
02:50:45,380 --> 02:50:47,216
It brought me to you.

1993
02:50:48,842 --> 02:50:51,303
And I'm thankful
for that, Rose.

1994
02:50:51,845 --> 02:50:53,180
I'm thankful.

1995
02:50:56,642 --> 02:50:57,726
You must...

1996
02:50:58,852 --> 02:51:00,854
...you must do me
this honor.

1997
02:51:03,857 --> 02:51:07,361
You must promise me
that you'll survive.

1998
02:51:09,363 --> 02:51:11,031
That you won't give up...

1999
02:51:12,199 --> 02:51:14,201
...no matter what happens.

2000
02:51:16,870 --> 02:51:19,206
No matter how hopeless.

2001
02:51:22,376 --> 02:51:24,545
Promise me now, Rose.

2002
02:51:26,713 --> 02:51:29,049
And never let go
of that promise.

2003
02:51:30,717 --> 02:51:32,052
I promise.

2004
02:51:34,179 --> 02:51:35,848
Never let go.

2005
02:51:38,725 --> 02:51:40,853
I'll never let go, Jack.

2006
02:51:43,564 --> 02:51:45,232
I'll never let go.

2007
02:52:09,339 --> 02:52:10,841
Right ahead, sir.

2008
02:52:14,011 --> 02:52:15,512
Oars!

2009
02:52:16,013 --> 02:52:17,681
Do you see any moving?

2010
02:52:18,682 --> 02:52:20,601
No, sir. None
moving, sir.

2011
02:52:21,185 --> 02:52:22,519
Check them.

2012
02:52:22,853 --> 02:52:24,354
Bring that oar up here.

2013
02:52:31,028 --> 02:52:32,029
Check them.
Make sure.

2014
02:52:33,447 --> 02:52:35,073
These are dead, sir.

2015
02:52:35,574 --> 02:52:36,742
Now, give way.

2016
02:52:37,201 --> 02:52:38,243
Ahead easy.

2017
02:52:45,042 --> 02:52:46,543
Careful with your oars.

2018
02:52:47,127 --> 02:52:48,170
Don't hit them.

2019
02:52:50,714 --> 02:52:53,050
Is there anyone
alive out there?

2020
02:52:54,551 --> 02:52:56,386
Can anyone hear me?

2021
02:52:58,555 --> 02:53:00,891
Is there anyone
alive out there?

2022
02:53:07,731 --> 02:53:08,941
We waited too long.

2023
02:53:12,861 --> 02:53:14,613
Well, keep checking them!

2024
02:53:14,738 --> 02:53:16,406
Keep looking!

2025
02:53:17,241 --> 02:53:19,743
Is there anyone
alive out there?

2026
02:53:23,247 --> 02:53:25,249
Can anyone hear me?

2027
02:53:36,426 --> 02:53:39,263
Come, Josephine...

2028
02:53:39,763 --> 02:53:44,268
...in my flying machine

2029
02:53:45,769 --> 02:53:48,981
And it's up she goes

2030
02:53:50,941 --> 02:53:52,943
Up she goes

2031
02:53:58,449 --> 02:54:00,617
Come, Josephine...

2032
02:54:02,953 --> 02:54:05,289
...in my flying...

2033
02:54:29,146 --> 02:54:30,481
Jack.

2034
02:54:48,332 --> 02:54:49,666
Jack.

2035
02:54:50,167 --> 02:54:51,502
There's a boat.

2036
02:55:04,681 --> 02:55:06,016
Jack.

2037
02:55:18,529 --> 02:55:20,531
There's a
boat, Jack.

2038
02:56:04,241 --> 02:56:05,576
Come back.

2039
02:56:06,743 --> 02:56:08,245
Come back.

2040
02:56:10,414 --> 02:56:11,748
Come back.

2041
02:56:12,916 --> 02:56:14,418
Come back.

2042
02:56:15,252 --> 02:56:16,753
Come back.

2043
02:56:17,588 --> 02:56:19,923
Come back.
Come back!

2044
02:56:21,425 --> 02:56:22,926
Hello!

2045
02:56:25,053 --> 02:56:26,930
Can anyone hear me?

2046
02:56:27,431 --> 02:56:29,099
There's nothing
here, sir.

2047
02:56:31,602 --> 02:56:32,936
Come back.

2048
02:56:34,438 --> 02:56:35,773
Come back.

2049
02:56:43,614 --> 02:56:45,115
I'll never let go.

2050
02:56:45,365 --> 02:56:46,700
I promise.

2051
02:57:29,785 --> 02:57:31,620
Come about!

2052
02:57:52,975 --> 02:57:56,812
Fifteen hundred people
went into the sea...

2053
02:57:57,146 --> 02:58:00,149
...when Titanic
sank from under us.

2054
02:58:01,984 --> 02:58:05,154
There were twenty
boats floating nearby...

2055
02:58:06,321 --> 02:58:08,657
...and only one came back.

2056
02:58:10,492 --> 02:58:11,618
One.

2057
02:58:13,328 --> 02:58:15,998
Six were saved
from the water...

2058
02:58:16,498 --> 02:58:18,167
...myself included.

2059
02:58:19,334 --> 02:58:20,627
Six...

2060
02:58:21,837 --> 02:58:23,714
...out of fifteen hundred.

2061
02:58:27,009 --> 02:58:28,343
Afterward...

2062
02:58:29,511 --> 02:58:31,513
...the seven hundred
people in the boats...

2063
02:58:32,306 --> 02:58:34,391
...had nothing to
do but wait.

2064
02:58:36,018 --> 02:58:37,686
Wait to die.

2065
02:58:38,187 --> 02:58:39,688
Wait to live.

2066
02:58:40,856 --> 02:58:43,025
Wait for an absolution...

2067
02:58:43,525 --> 02:58:45,360
...that would never come.

2068
02:59:49,591 --> 02:59:52,052
Sir, I don't think you'll find any
of your people down here.

2069
02:59:52,219 --> 02:59:53,637
It's all steerage.

2070
02:59:56,598 --> 03:00:00,144
His hair is reddish brown,
reddish brown, reddish brown.

2071
03:00:00,269 --> 03:00:01,645
White beard.

2072
03:00:02,104 --> 03:00:03,730
Isn't there another
passenger list?

2073
03:00:03,772 --> 03:00:04,898
There is no other list.

2074
03:00:05,065 --> 03:00:06,483
Perhaps he's on
another ship.

2075
03:00:06,775 --> 03:00:08,610
We're doing all we can,
ma'am. I'm so sorry.

2076
03:00:31,967 --> 03:00:34,636
That's the last time
I ever saw him.

2077
03:00:35,137 --> 03:00:38,640
He married, of course,
and inherited his millions.

2078
03:00:39,308 --> 03:00:42,811
But the Crash of '29 hit his interests hard...

2079
03:00:43,145 --> 03:00:45,439
...and he put a pistol in
his mouth that year.

2080
03:00:45,981 --> 03:00:47,816
Or so I read.

2081
03:01:00,662 --> 03:01:02,122
Can I take your name
please, love?

2082
03:01:05,167 --> 03:01:06,502
Dawson.

2083
03:01:08,670 --> 03:01:10,172
Rose Dawson.

2084
03:01:11,507 --> 03:01:12,674
Thank you.

2085
03:01:19,681 --> 03:01:21,809
We never found
anything on Jack.

2086
03:01:21,975 --> 03:01:23,894
There's no record
of him at all.

2087
03:01:24,520 --> 03:01:26,855
No, there wouldn't
be, would there?

2088
03:01:27,189 --> 03:01:29,900
And I've never spoken
of him until now.

2089
03:01:30,651 --> 03:01:31,693
Not to anyone.

2090
03:01:32,861 --> 03:01:34,863
Not even your
grandfather.

2091
03:01:35,197 --> 03:01:39,201
A woman's heart is a
deep ocean of secrets.

2092
03:01:40,035 --> 03:01:43,705
But now you know there was
a man named Jack Dawson...

2093
03:01:44,039 --> 03:01:46,041
...and that he saved me...

2094
03:01:46,375 --> 03:01:49,711
...in every way that
a person can be saved.

2095
03:01:51,713 --> 03:01:54,383
I don't even have
a picture of him.

2096
03:01:56,885 --> 03:02:00,722
He exists now only
in my memory.

2097
03:02:05,561 --> 03:02:09,064
Keldysh, Mir 2 on our
way to the surface.

2098
03:02:25,581 --> 03:02:28,375
I was saving this for when
I found the diamond.

2099
03:02:37,760 --> 03:02:39,261
I'm sorry.

2100
03:02:41,930 --> 03:02:43,432
Three years...

2101
03:02:44,099 --> 03:02:46,769
...I've thought of
nothing except Titanic.

2102
03:02:47,603 --> 03:02:49,438
But I never got it.

2103
03:02:52,566 --> 03:02:54,443
I never let it in.
